WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.500 --> 00:00:03.860
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:03.860 --> 00:00:06.510
- So it's my
pleasure to introduce

00:00:06.510 --> 00:00:08.370
the first panel of
this afternoon, which

00:00:08.370 --> 00:00:10.800
is on big data.

00:00:10.800 --> 00:00:13.530
I alluded to it this
morning, but there

00:00:13.530 --> 00:00:17.820
is an explosion of data at
every level of the organism

00:00:17.820 --> 00:00:21.900
to behavioral data, like
our cell phone usage, that

00:00:21.900 --> 00:00:24.570
can be used if you're
clever analytically,

00:00:24.570 --> 00:00:28.170
and that has its own
challenges, to really understand

00:00:28.170 --> 00:00:31.590
patterns of disease and
potentially prevent them.

00:00:31.590 --> 00:00:35.220
So to lead this panel our
moderator is Caroline Buckee.

00:00:35.220 --> 00:00:37.950
She is an assistant
professor of epidemiology

00:00:37.950 --> 00:00:40.800
at the Harvard Chan School of
Public Health, where she's also

00:00:40.800 --> 00:00:44.820
the associate director of the
Center for Communicable Disease

00:00:44.820 --> 00:00:46.260
Dynamics.

00:00:46.260 --> 00:00:49.590
Dr. Buckee's work at Harvard
uses mathematical models

00:00:49.590 --> 00:00:52.020
to bridge the biological
scales underlying malaria

00:00:52.020 --> 00:00:53.610
epidemiology.

00:00:53.610 --> 00:00:55.410
She works with
experimental researchers

00:00:55.410 --> 00:00:59.070
to understand the molecular
mechanisms within the host that

00:00:59.070 --> 00:01:00.840
underlie disease and infection.

00:01:00.840 --> 00:01:03.780
And uses both genomic
and mobile phone data

00:01:03.780 --> 00:01:06.210
to link these individual
level processes

00:01:06.210 --> 00:01:10.560
to understand population
level patterns of transit.

00:01:10.560 --> 00:01:12.893
Please join me in
welcoming Dr. Buckee.

00:01:12.893 --> 00:01:16.204
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:18.580 --> 00:01:21.490
- Thank you.

00:01:21.490 --> 00:01:24.280
The world is changing
very fast, as we all know.

00:01:24.280 --> 00:01:26.980
We've all seen those
exponential graphs

00:01:26.980 --> 00:01:28.900
showing population growth.

00:01:28.900 --> 00:01:32.260
But population density is
also rising very quickly.

00:01:32.260 --> 00:01:35.890
And as of 2014, more than half
the world's population was

00:01:35.890 --> 00:01:38.860
living in an urban
environment and projections

00:01:38.860 --> 00:01:40.510
suggest that over
the next 30 years

00:01:40.510 --> 00:01:43.990
we will add 2.5 billion people
to our urban environments,

00:01:43.990 --> 00:01:47.080
and 90% of those will
be in Asia and Africa.

00:01:47.080 --> 00:01:48.940
So there's nothing a
pathogen likes more

00:01:48.940 --> 00:01:52.480
than a densely populated slum.

00:01:52.480 --> 00:01:54.490
And I think that
really highlights

00:01:54.490 --> 00:01:57.010
some of the threads that
were brought up earlier today

00:01:57.010 --> 00:01:59.410
about the importance
of embedding all

00:01:59.410 --> 00:02:02.290
of our research in
the local populations

00:02:02.290 --> 00:02:05.890
and national control programs in
low and middle income settings.

00:02:05.890 --> 00:02:09.830
And in particular,
for capacity training.

00:02:09.830 --> 00:02:13.000
So this session is on big data.

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:14.650
Many of us don't
really like the term

00:02:14.650 --> 00:02:17.500
big data, although it's catchy.

00:02:17.500 --> 00:02:20.080
So I would like to reframe
this as a discussion

00:02:20.080 --> 00:02:23.710
about qualitatively new
types of data stream

00:02:23.710 --> 00:02:27.920
that are often at scale, at
the level of the population.

00:02:27.920 --> 00:02:30.700
And so yes, this requires
new computational challenges.

00:02:30.700 --> 00:02:33.220
But I think by labeling
things big data we

00:02:33.220 --> 00:02:37.240
can miss the fact that all
of these new data streams

00:02:37.240 --> 00:02:42.010
are embedded within
traditional small data that

00:02:42.010 --> 00:02:43.270
are absolutely essential.

00:02:43.270 --> 00:02:46.570
So epidemiological information
on the ground, the importance

00:02:46.570 --> 00:02:48.640
of community health
care workers,

00:02:48.640 --> 00:02:51.250
like was highlighted earlier
when we discussed Ebola,

00:02:51.250 --> 00:02:53.090
really can't be overstated.

00:02:53.090 --> 00:02:56.420
So we do have many
new opportunities.

00:02:56.420 --> 00:02:59.170
So I'm just going to give you
some numbers to kind of frame

00:02:59.170 --> 00:03:02.140
how fast the pace of
technology is changing.

00:03:02.140 --> 00:03:05.230
So it took on the order
of months or even years

00:03:05.230 --> 00:03:06.817
to sequence a
single human genome.

00:03:06.817 --> 00:03:08.650
In the year 2000 it
would have cost hundreds

00:03:08.650 --> 00:03:10.280
of millions of dollars.

00:03:10.280 --> 00:03:12.520
Now, it costs on
the order of $1,000.

00:03:12.520 --> 00:03:14.470
And we saw this morning
from Christian's talk

00:03:14.470 --> 00:03:16.930
that we can sequence
viral genomes which

00:03:16.930 --> 00:03:21.430
are much, much smaller than
that for $50, even less,

00:03:21.430 --> 00:03:23.630
over a very short time period.

00:03:23.630 --> 00:03:27.010
We also talked about CRISPR
and the promise of gene drive

00:03:27.010 --> 00:03:30.640
technologies for controlling
and containing diseases.

00:03:30.640 --> 00:03:33.700
So we have this opportunity to
really fundamentally rethink

00:03:33.700 --> 00:03:36.940
how we do diagnostics,
surveillance, and track

00:03:36.940 --> 00:03:39.760
epidemics for containment.

00:03:39.760 --> 00:03:43.471
Mobile phones, which we all
have now, except for some people

00:03:43.471 --> 00:03:44.470
don't have smart phones.

00:03:44.470 --> 00:03:48.010
But generally speaking,
everyone has a phone.

00:03:48.010 --> 00:03:52.810
So the World Bank estimates that
in 2000, 12 out of 100 people

00:03:52.810 --> 00:03:54.640
had mobile phone subscriptions.

00:03:54.640 --> 00:03:57.290
Now it's 101 out of 100
people have mobile phone

00:03:57.290 --> 00:03:58.600
subscriptions.

00:03:58.600 --> 00:04:00.250
Clearly the distribution
is not even,

00:04:00.250 --> 00:04:02.530
and some people have
multiple subscriptions.

00:04:02.530 --> 00:04:05.530
But increasingly, cell
phones are everywhere.

00:04:05.530 --> 00:04:08.140
And so not only
does it produce what

00:04:08.140 --> 00:04:11.110
we call digital exhaust data,
behavioral data about where

00:04:11.110 --> 00:04:13.570
everyone is, where they're
going, what they're doing,

00:04:13.570 --> 00:04:17.620
it also creates a tool to
engage directly with people

00:04:17.620 --> 00:04:19.269
and to educate them.

00:04:19.269 --> 00:04:21.970
Now of course, what comes
with that is also challenges.

00:04:21.970 --> 00:04:25.930
So we have this explosion of
disinformation, the importance

00:04:25.930 --> 00:04:28.510
of rumors in containing
epidemics and trying

00:04:28.510 --> 00:04:30.170
to reach people.

00:04:30.170 --> 00:04:34.930
And so I think it also brings
up this question about where

00:04:34.930 --> 00:04:37.040
we aim our solutions.

00:04:37.040 --> 00:04:40.000
So designing the perfect app
isn't going to work, clearly.

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:43.330
We need to have cultural
specific context when

00:04:43.330 --> 00:04:45.970
we think about engaging
populations around epidemic

00:04:45.970 --> 00:04:47.800
containment and surveillance.

00:04:47.800 --> 00:04:49.300
So I think the
challenges that we're

00:04:49.300 --> 00:04:52.240
going to discuss today that
come along with the promises

00:04:52.240 --> 00:04:56.350
that big data provide are to
do with the lack of analytics,

00:04:56.350 --> 00:05:00.190
the lack of validation, the
need to integrate these new data

00:05:00.190 --> 00:05:02.530
sources with
traditional epidemiology

00:05:02.530 --> 00:05:04.480
and national control programs.

00:05:04.480 --> 00:05:06.220
And then it also
brings up some issues

00:05:06.220 --> 00:05:08.830
that are age old problems for
public health practitioners

00:05:08.830 --> 00:05:11.650
like, how do we balance
individual rights, rights

00:05:11.650 --> 00:05:14.680
to privacy, with public health?

00:05:14.680 --> 00:05:17.920
And I would be interested to
hear your thoughts about that

00:05:17.920 --> 00:05:18.730
too.

00:05:18.730 --> 00:05:20.950
So our speakers, again,
you have their bios.

00:05:20.950 --> 00:05:24.010
Our speakers are going to
range from global health

00:05:24.010 --> 00:05:28.840
security and threats on a global
scale that are represented

00:05:28.840 --> 00:05:30.490
by emerging diseases.

00:05:30.490 --> 00:05:33.610
And then we're going to hear
about the national control

00:05:33.610 --> 00:05:35.620
programs and how we can
move them forward using

00:05:35.620 --> 00:05:37.930
new analytics and
new technologies.

00:05:37.930 --> 00:05:42.610
And then lastly, Ami is going
to discuss with us the promise

00:05:42.610 --> 00:05:44.320
of genomics for
helping us understand

00:05:44.320 --> 00:05:46.510
human health as an ecosystem.

00:05:46.510 --> 00:05:48.610
An integrated
system that reflects

00:05:48.610 --> 00:05:51.400
the dynamics of immune systems
and our microbial communities,

00:05:51.400 --> 00:05:53.890
and what that means for
developing new drugs

00:05:53.890 --> 00:05:55.570
and approaches to containment.

00:05:55.570 --> 00:05:58.080
So I will, without
further ado, I

00:05:58.080 --> 00:06:00.630
will introduce our first
speaker Jim Wilson.

00:06:00.630 --> 00:06:02.077
Please join me in welcoming him.

00:06:02.077 --> 00:06:05.416
[APPLAUSE]

00:06:08.278 --> 00:06:10.507
- OK.

00:06:10.507 --> 00:06:12.090
So we're going to
talk about something

00:06:12.090 --> 00:06:18.360
that is, I would say, a
little bit off the beaten path

00:06:18.360 --> 00:06:19.680
of typical public health.

00:06:19.680 --> 00:06:22.740
And this is the world where
public health intersects

00:06:22.740 --> 00:06:24.730
with national security.

00:06:24.730 --> 00:06:26.520
And I think this is
an important topic

00:06:26.520 --> 00:06:29.555
to discuss because,
just for context here,

00:06:29.555 --> 00:06:32.055
this is the first time I've
ever spoken about this publicly.

00:06:35.150 --> 00:06:37.260
I've been doing this
work for 25 years.

00:06:44.065 --> 00:06:47.590
What do I mean when I say
health security intelligence?

00:06:47.590 --> 00:06:49.240
Why do we need
this intelligence?

00:06:49.240 --> 00:06:52.570
I think your speakers from the
first panel amply displayed why

00:06:52.570 --> 00:06:55.420
we need effective intelligence.

00:06:55.420 --> 00:06:58.176
How is information used to
inform our intelligence?

00:06:58.176 --> 00:06:59.800
What do I mean when
I say intelligence?

00:06:59.800 --> 00:07:02.814
I'm not interested in people's
personal records, at all.

00:07:02.814 --> 00:07:04.480
I'm not interested
in named individuals.

00:07:04.480 --> 00:07:07.990
I'm interested in trends big
trends, scary trends, trends

00:07:07.990 --> 00:07:10.780
that are sometimes
very hard to detect.

00:07:10.780 --> 00:07:12.829
How do we use the intelligence?

00:07:12.829 --> 00:07:15.370
And what are the challenges with
health security intelligence

00:07:15.370 --> 00:07:16.161
in today's society?

00:07:16.161 --> 00:07:18.850
I will give you a hint, they're
the exact same challenges

00:07:18.850 --> 00:07:21.760
that Kevin outlined earlier,
as well as our first panel.

00:07:21.760 --> 00:07:24.070
This whole aspect of
information sharing,

00:07:24.070 --> 00:07:25.840
who gets to control
that information,

00:07:25.840 --> 00:07:28.270
all the games people play.

00:07:28.270 --> 00:07:31.110
You will find me to be a cynic.

00:07:31.110 --> 00:07:34.350
You will find me to be
very frustrated and angry

00:07:34.350 --> 00:07:36.750
with my own career
and my failure

00:07:36.750 --> 00:07:40.500
to convince our
government and the world

00:07:40.500 --> 00:07:42.130
to do the right damn thing.

00:07:45.340 --> 00:07:47.020
All right, here we go.

00:07:47.020 --> 00:07:50.740
Traditional public
health, and I'm

00:07:50.740 --> 00:07:52.960
going to upset a
couple folks here,

00:07:52.960 --> 00:07:56.410
as a discipline does tend
to be forensically oriented.

00:07:56.410 --> 00:07:59.740
There is an important
reason for that.

00:07:59.740 --> 00:08:03.400
You cannot have our CDC or
our public health officials

00:08:03.400 --> 00:08:06.430
expressing things that are
speculative to the public.

00:08:06.430 --> 00:08:08.940
You must have confidence.

00:08:08.940 --> 00:08:09.500
Right?

00:08:09.500 --> 00:08:10.550
We all in agreement?

00:08:10.550 --> 00:08:12.680
You don't want to have
questions about your CDC.

00:08:12.680 --> 00:08:15.860
You want to take their
word as almost the word

00:08:15.860 --> 00:08:18.910
from some divinity, right?

00:08:18.910 --> 00:08:23.030
To achieve that level of
confidence takes time,

00:08:23.030 --> 00:08:25.370
takes a lot of time.

00:08:25.370 --> 00:08:29.630
Unfortunately for us, we
continually run out of time.

00:08:29.630 --> 00:08:32.210
We don't have time
to screw around.

00:08:32.210 --> 00:08:35.559
We need to make decisions now.

00:08:35.559 --> 00:08:38.289
If I told you the real
stories behind the scenes

00:08:38.289 --> 00:08:40.270
about how we managed
to Ebola, how we

00:08:40.270 --> 00:08:43.982
managed Zika, how we managed
a lot of these issues--

00:08:43.982 --> 00:08:45.440
and there are books
out there like,

00:08:45.440 --> 00:08:48.220
And the Band Played
On about HIV.

00:08:48.220 --> 00:08:52.000
You will find that we've been
playing games for decades,

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:53.810
and it's very unfortunate.

00:08:53.810 --> 00:08:56.290
But some of those games are
important games to play.

00:08:56.290 --> 00:08:59.031
You need peer review, right?

00:08:59.031 --> 00:08:59.530
You do.

00:08:59.530 --> 00:09:03.400
You need to be sure of what
you're dealing with here.

00:09:03.400 --> 00:09:07.720
So there's a minimal
tolerance of false alarms.

00:09:07.720 --> 00:09:12.430
In our world however,
we embrace false alarms.

00:09:12.430 --> 00:09:16.270
We want to be on that bleeding
edge of alert notification.

00:09:16.270 --> 00:09:19.109
I am intolerant of people
playing games with information

00:09:19.109 --> 00:09:20.650
when we're dealing
with an event that

00:09:20.650 --> 00:09:23.530
could cause massive
socioeconomic disruption

00:09:23.530 --> 00:09:25.870
or scare the living
heck out of the public.

00:09:25.870 --> 00:09:28.630
I want resolution of uncertainty
as fast as we can get it.

00:09:28.630 --> 00:09:31.790
And I'm willing to
take false positives.

00:09:31.790 --> 00:09:34.500
Now that's a very different
perspective, it really is.

00:09:34.500 --> 00:09:37.900
And a totally
different work culture.

00:09:37.900 --> 00:09:41.610
In my world, I was dealing
with the time sensitive issues.

00:09:41.610 --> 00:09:44.890
The very bleeding edge of a flip
point where a community is just

00:09:44.890 --> 00:09:47.080
humming along in their
activities of daily living

00:09:47.080 --> 00:09:48.815
and all of a sudden,
somebody flinches.

00:09:53.150 --> 00:09:56.474
So the birth of health security
intelligence really began--

00:09:56.474 --> 00:09:57.890
and there have
been various groups

00:09:57.890 --> 00:10:00.740
that have looked at this from
intelligence perspectives

00:10:00.740 --> 00:10:04.906
since going back as far as
the Spanish flu of 1918.

00:10:04.906 --> 00:10:06.530
But they've done it
for various reasons

00:10:06.530 --> 00:10:09.230
and with different
purposes in mind.

00:10:09.230 --> 00:10:12.950
I actually started my
career trying to forecast

00:10:12.950 --> 00:10:14.900
Ebola using satellite imagery.

00:10:14.900 --> 00:10:16.460
But my sample size
was really small

00:10:16.460 --> 00:10:18.543
and I was having a hard
time publishing the paper.

00:10:21.420 --> 00:10:24.000
Because you want a robust
sample size, right?

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:26.194
You want to meet certain
criteria for publication.

00:10:26.194 --> 00:10:27.610
We just couldn't
get it out there.

00:10:27.610 --> 00:10:30.120
But I needed to get it out
there because I needed people

00:10:30.120 --> 00:10:31.722
to test the hypothesis.

00:10:31.722 --> 00:10:33.230
Right?

00:10:33.230 --> 00:10:36.980
So this is in the late
1990s, before we had bioRxiv

00:10:36.980 --> 00:10:39.200
and some of these
other systems to enable

00:10:39.200 --> 00:10:41.830
us to share that information.

00:10:41.830 --> 00:10:45.360
But when I walked around
our country trying

00:10:45.360 --> 00:10:48.750
to find the one agency that
actually has a watch cell that

00:10:48.750 --> 00:10:51.120
actually does,
indeed, do nothing

00:10:51.120 --> 00:10:53.340
but watch the entire
planet for bad things.

00:10:53.340 --> 00:10:55.940
I couldn't find it.

00:10:55.940 --> 00:10:58.122
And I say, I went everywhere.

00:10:58.122 --> 00:11:00.080
I even went to the
department of transportation

00:11:00.080 --> 00:11:02.370
in desperateness.

00:11:02.370 --> 00:11:05.430
Why don't we have a National
Weather Service equivalent

00:11:05.430 --> 00:11:07.960
for infectious disease?

00:11:07.960 --> 00:11:13.950
I am angry after 25 years
we still don't have it.

00:11:13.950 --> 00:11:16.830
So I tried to convince people.

00:11:16.830 --> 00:11:20.780
What would it take for us
to have one for the world?

00:11:20.780 --> 00:11:24.530
West Nile virus was the
beginning of that discourse.

00:11:24.530 --> 00:11:27.290
And I'm here to tell you that
West Nile unfortunately, sadly

00:11:27.290 --> 00:11:30.150
did not kill enough people.

00:11:30.150 --> 00:11:31.940
You have to kill people.

00:11:31.940 --> 00:11:33.200
You have to kill Americans.

00:11:33.200 --> 00:11:34.520
You've got to do
it fast, and you've

00:11:34.520 --> 00:11:35.910
got to do it in a nice
cluster, and you've

00:11:35.910 --> 00:11:37.250
got to get a good sample size.

00:11:37.250 --> 00:11:38.625
And you've got to
kill the young,

00:11:38.625 --> 00:11:40.815
and you've got to kill
working age adults.

00:11:40.815 --> 00:11:42.440
Think about it, what's
it going to take

00:11:42.440 --> 00:11:47.420
to get political willpower
to back something like that?

00:11:47.420 --> 00:11:50.600
What ultimately got us
started was actually SARS.

00:11:50.600 --> 00:11:53.960
Where our team actually looked
at some of these signatures

00:11:53.960 --> 00:11:56.480
that were actually reported
in publicly available

00:11:56.480 --> 00:12:00.350
Chinese media, and realized
that we actually missed plenty

00:12:00.350 --> 00:12:02.920
of heads up warning for months.

00:12:02.920 --> 00:12:04.920
Months.

00:12:04.920 --> 00:12:07.050
OK, I'm sorry the Chinese
actually didn't really

00:12:07.050 --> 00:12:08.130
hide a lot.

00:12:08.130 --> 00:12:11.490
There was a lot of information.

00:12:11.490 --> 00:12:13.812
Now, why did we miss it?

00:12:13.812 --> 00:12:16.270
Well, there's some pretty ugly
questions to be asked there,

00:12:16.270 --> 00:12:17.270
yes?

00:12:17.270 --> 00:12:20.990
4 1/2 months is what I'm talking
about in terms of the time

00:12:20.990 --> 00:12:22.250
delta.

00:12:22.250 --> 00:12:25.160
We've had alleged
bioweapon events, including

00:12:25.160 --> 00:12:28.190
one that I recently published
on the largest anthrax

00:12:28.190 --> 00:12:30.170
epidemic documented
in modern history

00:12:30.170 --> 00:12:35.600
during that counterinsurgency
in Rhodesia in the late 1970s.

00:12:35.600 --> 00:12:38.540
Interesting events that
shouldn't have gone unnoticed,

00:12:38.540 --> 00:12:40.904
that shouldn't have
gone unreported.

00:12:40.904 --> 00:12:42.320
Why aren't there
many publications

00:12:42.320 --> 00:12:45.220
about these events?

00:12:45.220 --> 00:12:48.280
Lab accidents, we've
had lab accidents, yes.

00:12:48.280 --> 00:12:51.040
Many of which have
not been reported.

00:12:51.040 --> 00:12:53.060
I think Kevins provided
us with ample hints

00:12:53.060 --> 00:12:56.440
of there is research going
on around this world.

00:12:56.440 --> 00:12:59.260
Are we aware of who's
doing what, where?

00:12:59.260 --> 00:13:02.170
Genetic manipulation
of H5N1 virus

00:13:02.170 --> 00:13:03.860
to get it to transmit
more efficiently

00:13:03.860 --> 00:13:07.372
is my popular favorite.

00:13:07.372 --> 00:13:09.080
Do we know if they've
had a lab accident?

00:13:09.080 --> 00:13:11.480
What happens if they
do have a lab accident?

00:13:11.480 --> 00:13:14.420
Do we have vaccine ready
on standby in case they do?

00:13:14.420 --> 00:13:16.977
Will it be able to be
deployed fast enough?

00:13:16.977 --> 00:13:18.560
Unfortunately, these
are the questions

00:13:18.560 --> 00:13:21.530
that we're stuck
with in my world.

00:13:21.530 --> 00:13:26.860
HIV/AIDS, took us a long
time to figure that one out.

00:13:26.860 --> 00:13:29.370
Venezuelan equine
encephalitis, that's

00:13:29.370 --> 00:13:31.470
an agent that is
mosquito transmitted very

00:13:31.470 --> 00:13:34.140
similar to some of the other
agents we've discussed today,

00:13:34.140 --> 00:13:36.630
causes pediatric encephalitis.

00:13:36.630 --> 00:13:41.007
We had a huge epizootic
in Venezuela for which

00:13:41.007 --> 00:13:42.090
we didn't receive warning.

00:13:42.090 --> 00:13:43.714
And there was a
convergence of the peak

00:13:43.714 --> 00:13:46.430
of the epidemic with the peak
of direct nonstop air traffic

00:13:46.430 --> 00:13:47.720
to Dade County, Florida.

00:13:50.230 --> 00:13:52.810
West Nile, well, that's
been robustly discussed

00:13:52.810 --> 00:13:56.140
by Tracy McNamara who's the
Bronx Zoo veterinarian who

00:13:56.140 --> 00:13:58.180
helped raise the alarm on that.

00:13:58.180 --> 00:13:59.890
And all of the
challenges she faced

00:13:59.890 --> 00:14:03.855
trying to get people to pay
attention to what's going on.

00:14:03.855 --> 00:14:05.480
And if you really
talk to Tracy, you'll

00:14:05.480 --> 00:14:10.150
find out that later, she had a
really hard time getting a job.

00:14:10.150 --> 00:14:11.869
She is a national
hero in my opinion,

00:14:11.869 --> 00:14:13.160
she should have gotten a medal.

00:14:15.810 --> 00:14:17.140
SARS, we already talked about.

00:14:17.140 --> 00:14:21.430
MERS, when was the first time
MERS was really detected?

00:14:21.430 --> 00:14:24.156
Wasn't in the kingdom
of Saudi Arabia.

00:14:24.156 --> 00:14:26.840
It was in Jordan.

00:14:26.840 --> 00:14:30.050
It too, was blatantly
apparent to any analyst who

00:14:30.050 --> 00:14:34.440
was monitoring in the native
vernacular, or Arabic media,

00:14:34.440 --> 00:14:37.400
where they talked about an
unusual, atypical, fatal

00:14:37.400 --> 00:14:41.040
illness killing ICU
health care workers.

00:14:41.040 --> 00:14:42.120
Cholera, Haiti.

00:14:42.120 --> 00:14:45.320
I was asked not to
reveal my suspicion

00:14:45.320 --> 00:14:48.240
that the UN Mirabi base was the
source of the cholera disaster.

00:14:53.430 --> 00:14:55.740
My response to that
was, if we believe

00:14:55.740 --> 00:15:00.880
the UN to be the epitome of
the world, then act like it.

00:15:00.880 --> 00:15:02.830
It's called corporate
responsibility.

00:15:02.830 --> 00:15:07.710
It was an accident,
do not deny it.

00:15:07.710 --> 00:15:08.824
Ebola.

00:15:08.824 --> 00:15:10.990
How long was it on the
ground before we were finally

00:15:10.990 --> 00:15:12.370
able to mount a response?

00:15:12.370 --> 00:15:14.124
chikungunya, zika.

00:15:14.124 --> 00:15:16.165
This is a pattern it's
been going on for decades.

00:15:18.760 --> 00:15:20.310
So, targeting.

00:15:20.310 --> 00:15:24.120
So in our world we really are
focused on a subset of disease,

00:15:24.120 --> 00:15:27.750
the things that move very
quickly are locally unfamiliar.

00:15:27.750 --> 00:15:30.317
This speaks to diagnostics,
availability of infrastructure

00:15:30.317 --> 00:15:30.900
on the ground.

00:15:30.900 --> 00:15:32.910
It has to be clinically
significant, right?

00:15:32.910 --> 00:15:34.260
Can't be a mild disease.

00:15:34.260 --> 00:15:35.220
Ideally, it kills.

00:15:35.220 --> 00:15:36.120
Ideally, it maims.

00:15:36.120 --> 00:15:38.730
Ideally, it marks the
individual so that any layperson

00:15:38.730 --> 00:15:40.530
can see what's going on.

00:15:40.530 --> 00:15:42.030
You have to affect
a certain segment

00:15:42.030 --> 00:15:43.950
of the population, as
I've hinted at before:

00:15:43.950 --> 00:15:45.930
children, working age adults.

00:15:45.930 --> 00:15:48.480
If it affects the elderly,
unfortunately that gets buried.

00:15:48.480 --> 00:15:51.110
People don't talk about
illnesses in the elderly,

00:15:51.110 --> 00:15:54.540
worldwide, like they do
with working age adults.

00:15:54.540 --> 00:15:56.247
Problems with access
to diagnostics

00:15:56.247 --> 00:15:57.080
and countermeasures.

00:15:57.080 --> 00:15:59.930
So if we don't have a vaccine,
that's concerning to us.

00:15:59.930 --> 00:16:01.680
If you don't have an
effective antibiotic.

00:16:01.680 --> 00:16:04.429
Efficient transmission
is a big one, right?

00:16:04.429 --> 00:16:05.970
And that has to do
with the dynamics.

00:16:05.970 --> 00:16:08.300
Do we have herd immunity
on the ground or not?

00:16:08.300 --> 00:16:09.840
The data focus.

00:16:09.840 --> 00:16:12.960
We use global media.

00:16:12.960 --> 00:16:17.460
Now, I'm going to tell you
flat out, no company on Earth

00:16:17.460 --> 00:16:21.790
has a full grasp of the
entire global output of media.

00:16:21.790 --> 00:16:24.060
If you think ProMed
does it, guess again.

00:16:24.060 --> 00:16:26.730
If you think Google
does it, guess again.

00:16:26.730 --> 00:16:30.150
OK, Rupert Murdoch has played
actually quite a strong role

00:16:30.150 --> 00:16:32.897
in actually restricting our
access to media over time,

00:16:32.897 --> 00:16:34.480
so you have to pay
for everything now.

00:16:34.480 --> 00:16:37.067
So now the costs have increased.

00:16:37.067 --> 00:16:38.900
We had to monitor, just
to give you an idea,

00:16:38.900 --> 00:16:43.430
we had 50 full-time analysts
who spoke 50 languages

00:16:43.430 --> 00:16:44.690
as their primary language.

00:16:44.690 --> 00:16:49.790
That's what it took to get at
the barest tip of this iceberg.

00:16:49.790 --> 00:16:52.430
We had 5,000 live
events on the radar

00:16:52.430 --> 00:16:54.410
a day that we had
to keep an eye on.

00:16:54.410 --> 00:16:58.610
5,000 that were threated.

00:16:58.610 --> 00:17:01.245
And you've got to pick which
one of those 5,000 events

00:17:01.245 --> 00:17:03.203
that you're actually
going to pick up the phone

00:17:03.203 --> 00:17:07.790
and put your career on the
line and call somebody about.

00:17:07.790 --> 00:17:09.619
Tough work.

00:17:09.619 --> 00:17:11.325
And human networks.

00:17:11.325 --> 00:17:12.700
And really what
you're looking at

00:17:12.700 --> 00:17:16.420
is you're tipping and
queuing, tipping and queuing.

00:17:16.420 --> 00:17:20.159
And it's a constant dialogue,
it's a constant conversation.

00:17:20.159 --> 00:17:22.450
And you're having these
conversations with researchers,

00:17:22.450 --> 00:17:25.990
with physicians, with
journalists, with anyone

00:17:25.990 --> 00:17:28.840
who is close to the
action to try to say, hey,

00:17:28.840 --> 00:17:31.450
is this something
or is this nothing?

00:17:31.450 --> 00:17:33.940
At a time when we have
no epidemiological data.

00:17:33.940 --> 00:17:37.060
At a time when we might not
have any diagnostic information

00:17:37.060 --> 00:17:39.670
at all other than
people are dying.

00:17:39.670 --> 00:17:44.170
Or there's a report that people
panic evacuated a village.

00:17:44.170 --> 00:17:46.540
The bias, of course,
when you're dealing

00:17:46.540 --> 00:17:49.000
with data of any kind in
the electronic environment

00:17:49.000 --> 00:17:51.000
is, of course, where
is there infrastructure

00:17:51.000 --> 00:17:53.050
to support that data?

00:17:53.050 --> 00:17:57.190
So we knew very well that it
tends to follow this city light

00:17:57.190 --> 00:17:59.960
map, which should make sense.

00:17:59.960 --> 00:18:02.930
It's where you have
electricity, right?

00:18:02.930 --> 00:18:05.180
So in this analysis and
dissemination piece,

00:18:05.180 --> 00:18:09.320
we have used forecasting
tools for decades.

00:18:09.320 --> 00:18:12.450
So if anybody tells you that
we cannot forecast infectious

00:18:12.450 --> 00:18:15.380
disease, I'm here to tell you
that's just a blatant lie.

00:18:15.380 --> 00:18:16.250
It ain't true.

00:18:16.250 --> 00:18:16.790
We do.

00:18:16.790 --> 00:18:19.160
We have been for a long time.

00:18:19.160 --> 00:18:20.330
How do we use it?

00:18:20.330 --> 00:18:24.590
We use it to set the hypothesis
when we're tracking something

00:18:24.590 --> 00:18:26.390
in the real time space.

00:18:26.390 --> 00:18:28.670
We say, OK, I expect
to see that we're

00:18:28.670 --> 00:18:31.580
about to enter cholera season.

00:18:31.580 --> 00:18:34.337
I'm also forecasting the
entire social response

00:18:34.337 --> 00:18:35.420
pattern in that community.

00:18:35.420 --> 00:18:36.650
I know what they're going to do.

00:18:36.650 --> 00:18:38.066
What countermeasures
they're going

00:18:38.066 --> 00:18:40.470
to deploy, how they talk
about it in the media,

00:18:40.470 --> 00:18:42.860
whether or not there's social
anxiety, whether or not

00:18:42.860 --> 00:18:44.900
the hospital gets overwhelmed.

00:18:44.900 --> 00:18:48.322
We have all that information
and we know what to expect.

00:18:48.322 --> 00:18:50.030
So therefore, if you
know what to expect,

00:18:50.030 --> 00:18:52.580
you can recognize deviations.

00:18:52.580 --> 00:18:55.580
And you can recognize
when, uh-oh, that train

00:18:55.580 --> 00:18:57.620
seems to be coming
off the rails here.

00:18:57.620 --> 00:18:59.360
What's going on?

00:18:59.360 --> 00:19:01.670
Signal processing, I've
kind of hinted to that.

00:19:01.670 --> 00:19:04.520
That's the recognition of an
anomalous signature pattern,

00:19:04.520 --> 00:19:06.820
or an anomalous pattern that's
appearing in the system.

00:19:06.820 --> 00:19:09.660
There's a myriad of
different ways to do that.

00:19:09.660 --> 00:19:11.210
We have pattern libraries.

00:19:11.210 --> 00:19:13.521
So there's an Ebola signature.

00:19:13.521 --> 00:19:15.020
One of our speakers
from the morning

00:19:15.020 --> 00:19:17.930
was talking about the
Nigerian experience.

00:19:17.930 --> 00:19:20.840
That signature
looked like a country

00:19:20.840 --> 00:19:23.990
that is well adapted to
handling those kinds of issues.

00:19:23.990 --> 00:19:26.120
Whereas the signature of
a country that has never

00:19:26.120 --> 00:19:28.460
encountered Ebola before
with no infrastructure it,

00:19:28.460 --> 00:19:31.640
to us, looks like a heart
attack, wild fluctuations

00:19:31.640 --> 00:19:33.530
of indicators.

00:19:33.530 --> 00:19:36.260
Sensitization, desensitization
of human networks.

00:19:36.260 --> 00:19:39.200
We will actually ramp up entire
global networks of people

00:19:39.200 --> 00:19:42.260
to watch for something, and
then tamp them down again.

00:19:42.260 --> 00:19:44.660
Now, the tamping down is
a really important piece

00:19:44.660 --> 00:19:46.580
that people really
don't appreciate.

00:19:46.580 --> 00:19:51.440
I spend, actually, 98% of my
time home calming people down.

00:19:51.440 --> 00:19:53.300
Indication warning
methodology is really

00:19:53.300 --> 00:19:55.940
what we're talking about
here, which is a Cold War

00:19:55.940 --> 00:19:57.740
intelligence
analytic methodology

00:19:57.740 --> 00:20:00.200
and it's available
for you to review

00:20:00.200 --> 00:20:01.260
in the public literature.

00:20:01.260 --> 00:20:02.630
Now, here's an example.

00:20:02.630 --> 00:20:06.200
So we manage the Japan
Medical Intelligence Center.

00:20:06.200 --> 00:20:09.710
These are actual
forecasts for legionella,

00:20:09.710 --> 00:20:12.290
carbapenum-resistant
gram negatives, which

00:20:12.290 --> 00:20:14.960
is a gram negative
bacteria that is

00:20:14.960 --> 00:20:18.225
resistant to one of our end of
line categories of antibiotics.

00:20:18.225 --> 00:20:21.770
I'm, also, side note, very much
into anti-microbial resistance

00:20:21.770 --> 00:20:23.240
tracking.

00:20:23.240 --> 00:20:25.860
And EHEC, which is a
disease we often see--

00:20:25.860 --> 00:20:28.565
or, not often,
thank god not often,

00:20:28.565 --> 00:20:32.390
a disease we occasionally
see in pediatrics.

00:20:32.390 --> 00:20:36.740
So the point here is, I
have a different demand

00:20:36.740 --> 00:20:37.550
for forecasting.

00:20:37.550 --> 00:20:40.370
I just want to know if we're
about to hit the season or not

00:20:40.370 --> 00:20:43.820
across dozens of diseases,
down to the prefecture level,

00:20:43.820 --> 00:20:45.560
down to the community level.

00:20:45.560 --> 00:20:49.220
And we have this information
across multiple countries.

00:20:49.220 --> 00:20:50.820
It does exist.

00:20:50.820 --> 00:20:52.870
Here's for Nevada.

00:20:52.870 --> 00:20:56.090
And on the left
side here, this is

00:20:56.090 --> 00:21:00.560
an example of an unusual
fall outbreak of H3N2.

00:21:00.560 --> 00:21:02.120
That's a seasonal
influenza and we

00:21:02.120 --> 00:21:03.650
were able to recognize it
very quickly because we had

00:21:03.650 --> 00:21:04.920
the baselines for influenza.

00:21:04.920 --> 00:21:06.830
So a lot of this
information is very

00:21:06.830 --> 00:21:09.770
reminiscent of what already
happens in epidemiology.

00:21:09.770 --> 00:21:11.630
We know what the
seasons are, right?

00:21:11.630 --> 00:21:14.090
We do build
statistical baselines.

00:21:14.090 --> 00:21:16.889
The question is, so what?

00:21:16.889 --> 00:21:18.680
How do you interface
with this information?

00:21:18.680 --> 00:21:20.000
How do you communicate
with people?

00:21:20.000 --> 00:21:21.710
And how do you blend it with
your awareness of what's

00:21:21.710 --> 00:21:22.880
happening in the community?

00:21:22.880 --> 00:21:25.460
And in this case on the
left, what happened was

00:21:25.460 --> 00:21:27.590
physicians were recommending
the influenza vaccine

00:21:27.590 --> 00:21:31.160
to older adults in December
because of waning immunity.

00:21:31.160 --> 00:21:33.140
The vaccine protective
period does not

00:21:33.140 --> 00:21:34.520
last as long in older adults.

00:21:34.520 --> 00:21:36.420
And so rightfully so
our community said,

00:21:36.420 --> 00:21:39.364
well, just wait until
December to get that vaccine.

00:21:39.364 --> 00:21:41.030
Well, we had four
fatalities due to type

00:21:41.030 --> 00:21:44.310
A influenza by
mid-October that year.

00:21:44.310 --> 00:21:46.702
And it was actually
a warning failure.

00:21:46.702 --> 00:21:49.160
And I got in a world of trouble
with my local public health

00:21:49.160 --> 00:21:51.960
people for pointing that out.

00:21:51.960 --> 00:21:54.830
RSV, you see that peak
there, that red line

00:21:54.830 --> 00:21:56.846
goes above our forecast band.

00:21:56.846 --> 00:21:58.970
That's a point where I
actually picked up the phone

00:21:58.970 --> 00:22:00.594
and called our
pediatric intensive care

00:22:00.594 --> 00:22:04.430
unit to make sure that our
soul PICU in the county

00:22:04.430 --> 00:22:06.766
wasn't getting overwhelmed.

00:22:06.766 --> 00:22:08.390
Are they calling up
backup ventilators,

00:22:08.390 --> 00:22:09.181
this kind of thing.

00:22:09.181 --> 00:22:12.170
So it's very important to kind
of put your data in context

00:22:12.170 --> 00:22:13.670
with your infrastructure.

00:22:13.670 --> 00:22:14.490
What's happening?

00:22:14.490 --> 00:22:16.200
Are we able to respond?

00:22:16.200 --> 00:22:18.170
Attribution.

00:22:18.170 --> 00:22:19.730
So this is the
actual email that I

00:22:19.730 --> 00:22:22.010
sent to 1,000 people
on the ground in Haiti

00:22:22.010 --> 00:22:24.500
about our suspicions
about the Mirabi base.

00:22:24.500 --> 00:22:27.350
I don't expect you to
be able to read it.

00:22:27.350 --> 00:22:30.080
But the point here is
that this was basically

00:22:30.080 --> 00:22:34.910
the culmination of this kind of
messy world of data gathering

00:22:34.910 --> 00:22:37.140
and human conversation.

00:22:37.140 --> 00:22:40.160
This was the tip where
we knew that we weren't

00:22:40.160 --> 00:22:43.314
dealing with endemic
Haitian cholera

00:22:43.314 --> 00:22:44.480
as some people were arguing.

00:22:44.480 --> 00:22:47.210
That we were actually dealing
with an imported virgin soil

00:22:47.210 --> 00:22:51.620
epidemic of Nepalese cholera,
whole different animal.

00:22:51.620 --> 00:22:53.990
And had national security
implications from the Haitian

00:22:53.990 --> 00:22:55.850
government point of view.

00:22:55.850 --> 00:22:56.990
Signal recognition.

00:22:56.990 --> 00:22:59.600
So how did we provide
the tip off on swine flu?

00:22:59.600 --> 00:23:00.980
Well, that was
open source media.

00:23:04.270 --> 00:23:09.760
Unfortunately for us, we
ran into some crossed wires

00:23:09.760 --> 00:23:12.460
with CDC who didn't
want to tell the press

00:23:12.460 --> 00:23:15.490
and acknowledge that we had
given them this information.

00:23:15.490 --> 00:23:18.860
We lost a $10 million
company over this.

00:23:18.860 --> 00:23:23.050
And I sent another
50 analysts home.

00:23:23.050 --> 00:23:24.370
Challenges.

00:23:24.370 --> 00:23:26.800
Well, as I've hinted,
this is a direct challenge

00:23:26.800 --> 00:23:28.577
to established bureaucracies.

00:23:28.577 --> 00:23:30.160
There are many
disagreements regarding

00:23:30.160 --> 00:23:31.930
what is considered
an alert priority.

00:23:31.930 --> 00:23:35.830
I've spent my career playing
Cassandra, the Greek tragedy

00:23:35.830 --> 00:23:37.780
of being cursed with
the ability of forecast

00:23:37.780 --> 00:23:39.029
and no one will listen to you.

00:23:42.660 --> 00:23:45.000
Failure by bureaucracies
to use the intelligence.

00:23:45.000 --> 00:23:47.100
I've seen this over, and
over, and over again.

00:23:47.100 --> 00:23:49.350
I'm tired of seeing it.

00:23:49.350 --> 00:23:51.600
Lack of understanding what
to do with the information.

00:23:51.600 --> 00:23:53.580
Well, OK, that's an
important challenge, right?

00:23:53.580 --> 00:23:55.770
That perhaps I can help with.

00:23:55.770 --> 00:23:56.735
Information control.

00:23:56.735 --> 00:23:58.860
If you think that people
don't control information,

00:23:58.860 --> 00:24:00.450
you're not living in reality.

00:24:00.450 --> 00:24:01.710
Everyone does it.

00:24:01.710 --> 00:24:03.720
And they do it in
my own locality.

00:24:03.720 --> 00:24:06.300
OK, I see hospitals hiding
information all the time,

00:24:06.300 --> 00:24:08.400
about drug resistance
for instance.

00:24:08.400 --> 00:24:10.440
And of course,
denial and deception.

00:24:10.440 --> 00:24:13.140
The funny thing is, if you ask
anyone in the national security

00:24:13.140 --> 00:24:15.600
committee they will put
that last bullet first.

00:24:15.600 --> 00:24:19.290
Saying, well, the state actor
is suppressing information.

00:24:19.290 --> 00:24:21.300
The hardest time I've
had getting information

00:24:21.300 --> 00:24:22.950
has nothing to do
with that, it has

00:24:22.950 --> 00:24:24.215
to do with my own local folks.

00:24:27.690 --> 00:24:29.350
It's the pogo cartoon, right?

00:24:29.350 --> 00:24:30.510
Who's the real enemy here?

00:24:30.510 --> 00:24:31.060
Challenges.

00:24:31.060 --> 00:24:33.890
Academic and
operations disconnect.

00:24:33.890 --> 00:24:36.670
So it's very hard
to have somebody

00:24:36.670 --> 00:24:39.760
like me sit in on a
collaborative research group

00:24:39.760 --> 00:24:41.470
to give them guidance
and say, look, this

00:24:41.470 --> 00:24:43.210
is what's really important.

00:24:43.210 --> 00:24:46.850
If you go down this road,
honestly, great paper.

00:24:46.850 --> 00:24:49.650
You get your PhD thesis but we
won't be able to put it to use,

00:24:49.650 --> 00:24:52.330
and there are all kinds
of reasons for that.

00:24:52.330 --> 00:24:54.490
There's an operations/policy
disconnect.

00:24:54.490 --> 00:24:55.990
I hate this.

00:24:55.990 --> 00:24:58.540
This is the thing that
actually is driving me squarely

00:24:58.540 --> 00:25:00.670
into insanity.

00:25:00.670 --> 00:25:03.250
We keep seeing policy
drafted out of Washington

00:25:03.250 --> 00:25:06.160
and it's quite clear that the
people who drafted the policy

00:25:06.160 --> 00:25:10.010
have never done
this work before.

00:25:10.010 --> 00:25:12.240
Transparent accountability.

00:25:12.240 --> 00:25:14.700
I've just hinted at multiple
intelligence failures.

00:25:14.700 --> 00:25:17.920
When was the last time we had
an open congressional session

00:25:17.920 --> 00:25:21.040
where we sort of reviewed
who knew what, when,

00:25:21.040 --> 00:25:24.070
and why didn't you
share that information?

00:25:24.070 --> 00:25:26.990
Time for that to
change, I think.

00:25:26.990 --> 00:25:29.840
Substantial inability to provide
balanced risk assessment.

00:25:29.840 --> 00:25:35.570
So this hints at our culture's
tendency to hype things.

00:25:35.570 --> 00:25:37.130
