00:28:40.390 --> 00:28:42.520
Next speaker is Jess Metcalf.

00:28:42.520 --> 00:28:44.470
She is an assistant
professor at Princeton.

00:28:44.470 --> 00:28:46.570
You can read her
bio in your book.

00:28:46.570 --> 00:28:48.700
And she's going
to talk about how

00:28:48.700 --> 00:28:52.240
we can move national control
programs forward using modeling

00:28:52.240 --> 00:28:55.980
and new technologies.

00:28:55.980 --> 00:28:56.990
- Hi.

00:28:56.990 --> 00:28:58.499
So it's a great
pleasure to be here.

00:28:58.499 --> 00:29:00.290
I'm going to talk about
how we can actually

00:29:00.290 --> 00:29:03.110
connect some of
these new, exciting

00:29:03.110 --> 00:29:06.200
and to use the term
big data streams,

00:29:06.200 --> 00:29:09.690
to public health questions.

00:29:09.690 --> 00:29:12.870
And I'm going to focus my
discussion around measles.

00:29:12.870 --> 00:29:15.630
So measles is a directly
transmitted, completely

00:29:15.630 --> 00:29:16.860
immunizing infection.

00:29:16.860 --> 00:29:19.110
So that means for someone
to give someone else measles

00:29:19.110 --> 00:29:20.700
they have to be in proximity.

00:29:20.700 --> 00:29:24.570
And once you've had measles,
you'll never have it again.

00:29:24.570 --> 00:29:26.490
So it has a very
simple life cycle.

00:29:26.490 --> 00:29:28.320
Individuals tend to
be born susceptible.

00:29:28.320 --> 00:29:30.395
They then become
infected, and then recover

00:29:30.395 --> 00:29:31.520
and are protected for life.

00:29:34.300 --> 00:29:40.915
We have a safe, inexpensive, and
completely immunizing vaccine.

00:29:40.915 --> 00:29:42.880
And since the case
fatality rate for measles

00:29:42.880 --> 00:29:47.200
can be extremely high, as high
as 20% in low resource settings

00:29:47.200 --> 00:29:50.920
and in catastrophes, and because
the consequences of measles

00:29:50.920 --> 00:29:53.140
can be so bad,
measles vaccination

00:29:53.140 --> 00:29:55.630
has been referred to as a
best buy in public health.

00:29:58.820 --> 00:30:03.050
Following successful eradication
of smallpox and polio,

00:30:03.050 --> 00:30:05.120
the Pan American
Health Organization

00:30:05.120 --> 00:30:09.860
decided to target measles
elimination in 1994.

00:30:09.860 --> 00:30:12.980
A combination of
routine vaccination

00:30:12.980 --> 00:30:16.880
with large campaigns designed
to both interrupt transmission

00:30:16.880 --> 00:30:19.670
and maintain high
population immunity

00:30:19.670 --> 00:30:21.860
meant that this was
achieved within a decade.

00:30:21.860 --> 00:30:23.260
It was a very
remarkable success.

00:30:25.910 --> 00:30:28.550
In the rest of the
world, the situation

00:30:28.550 --> 00:30:31.020
was not so successful.

00:30:31.020 --> 00:30:33.080
So the x-axis on all
these graphs is time

00:30:33.080 --> 00:30:35.270
and the y-axis is
numbers of cases.

00:30:35.270 --> 00:30:37.520
And you can see that
red line is Paho.

00:30:37.520 --> 00:30:40.210
Afro is the African WHO region.

00:30:40.210 --> 00:30:43.260
And WPR is the West
Pacific region.

00:30:43.260 --> 00:30:44.870
They're falling
much more slowly.

00:30:44.870 --> 00:30:47.270
Although there were substantial
gains at the beginning,

00:30:47.270 --> 00:30:50.160
progress has been interrupted.

00:30:50.160 --> 00:30:51.910
And we know why, partly.

00:30:51.910 --> 00:30:54.960
There is considerable inequity
in vaccination coverage

00:30:54.960 --> 00:30:56.780
across the globe.

00:30:56.780 --> 00:31:00.410
The yellow countries on
this plot in around 2011

00:31:00.410 --> 00:31:01.660
had coverage of less than 80%.

00:31:04.170 --> 00:31:05.880
Of course, these
national statistics

00:31:05.880 --> 00:31:08.820
also conceal a lot of
important heterogeneity.

00:31:08.820 --> 00:31:12.210
And even in countries that
seem to be doing really well,

00:31:12.210 --> 00:31:15.340
there have been large,
unexpected outbreaks.

00:31:15.340 --> 00:31:17.130
So this is an example
of one in Malawi

00:31:17.130 --> 00:31:18.900
that had a well-performing
system and very

00:31:18.900 --> 00:31:22.230
few cases for about a
decade, and then experienced

00:31:22.230 --> 00:31:26.450
this large late age
outbreak in 2010.

00:31:26.450 --> 00:31:27.510
And it made sense.

00:31:27.510 --> 00:31:28.590
We know why that happens.

00:31:28.590 --> 00:31:31.290
Vaccination coverage was
good, but not perfect.

00:31:31.290 --> 00:31:33.669
So every year, a certain
number of children

00:31:33.669 --> 00:31:35.460
were not being immunized
and they were also

00:31:35.460 --> 00:31:37.800
escaping infection because
we had successfully

00:31:37.800 --> 00:31:39.840
reduced transmission.

00:31:39.840 --> 00:31:42.270
And that meant that
when the infection came,

00:31:42.270 --> 00:31:44.520
there was this large outbreak.

00:31:44.520 --> 00:31:47.340
We used to think that measles
was so transmissible-- it

00:31:47.340 --> 00:31:49.170
is so transmissible--
that there was

00:31:49.170 --> 00:31:52.540
no point trying to intervene
once the epidemic could taken

00:31:52.540 --> 00:31:53.527
off.

00:31:53.527 --> 00:31:55.110
We know through
carefully modeling now

00:31:55.110 --> 00:31:56.850
that that's not the case.

00:31:56.850 --> 00:32:02.457
Outbreak reactive vaccination
is now indicated by WHO.

00:32:02.457 --> 00:32:04.290
And of course, it's
even better if you could

00:32:04.290 --> 00:32:06.150
have anticipated this outbreak.

00:32:06.150 --> 00:32:09.312
If two months, or three months
before the measles outbreak

00:32:09.312 --> 00:32:10.770
had kicked off in
Malawi you'd been

00:32:10.770 --> 00:32:12.990
able to reach the
population and vaccinate it,

00:32:12.990 --> 00:32:15.680
you could have averted many,
many cases, potentially.

00:32:15.680 --> 00:32:18.800
And thus, deaths and
thus the morbidity.

00:32:18.800 --> 00:32:20.270
But what would we
need to do that?

00:32:20.270 --> 00:32:22.589
We need two pieces to
do that successfully.

00:32:22.589 --> 00:32:24.380
And the first is that
we need to understand

00:32:24.380 --> 00:32:26.360
the landscape of immunity.

00:32:26.360 --> 00:32:31.490
We need to know who's protected
from infection and who isn't.

00:32:31.490 --> 00:32:34.160
In this particular example,
the person in red is infected

00:32:34.160 --> 00:32:36.560
and I've set this up with R0.

00:32:36.560 --> 00:32:38.939
So a number of new
infections of around two.

00:32:38.939 --> 00:32:40.730
So it infects two other
people, but there's

00:32:40.730 --> 00:32:42.500
a third person who's immune.

00:32:42.500 --> 00:32:45.320
And as it progresses and
as the pathogen progresses,

00:32:45.320 --> 00:32:47.400
more of the population
is protected.

00:32:47.400 --> 00:32:49.469
If we vaccinate
effectively, everybody

00:32:49.469 --> 00:32:51.260
should have that little
blue shield on them

00:32:51.260 --> 00:32:54.520
and the pathogen should
not be able to spread.

00:32:54.520 --> 00:32:56.440
To understand the
landscape for immunity,

00:32:56.440 --> 00:33:00.610
we therefore need to understand
both the scale of heterogeneity

00:33:00.610 --> 00:33:03.190
in local demographics, because
the source of new susceptible

00:33:03.190 --> 00:33:06.700
individuals is births, but
also, the history of vaccination

00:33:06.700 --> 00:33:09.472
and infection.

00:33:09.472 --> 00:33:10.930
There's another
piece that we need,

00:33:10.930 --> 00:33:13.180
and that is that we need to
understand human mobility.

00:33:13.180 --> 00:33:17.890
So we need to understand if you
have successfully eliminated

00:33:17.890 --> 00:33:20.470
measles in a particular
location but you're not

00:33:20.470 --> 00:33:23.350
vaccinating everybody so
susceptibles can build up.

00:33:23.350 --> 00:33:25.600
You might still get
away with it for a bit

00:33:25.600 --> 00:33:28.210
because the only way measles
is going to arrive in your city

00:33:28.210 --> 00:33:31.102
or your district is if someone
with measles turns up there.

00:33:31.102 --> 00:33:32.560
So we need to
understand how people

00:33:32.560 --> 00:33:34.480
are moving around the
landscape in order

00:33:34.480 --> 00:33:38.890
to grapple with understanding
the landscape of immunity

00:33:38.890 --> 00:33:42.950
and mobility to predict
when outbreaks would occur.

00:33:42.950 --> 00:33:45.730
So what we wanted to do, and
Caroline was part of this work,

00:33:45.730 --> 00:33:48.790
was see if we could figure
out retrospectively using

00:33:48.790 --> 00:33:51.610
all the tools we had available
could we have got ahead

00:33:51.610 --> 00:33:54.470
of an example
historical outbreak.

00:33:54.470 --> 00:33:56.260
And the example
outbreak we used was

00:33:56.260 --> 00:34:01.040
one that happened in
2010-12 in Pakistan.

00:34:01.040 --> 00:34:05.020
So again, x-axis
years, y-axis cases.

00:34:05.020 --> 00:34:07.570
So we mustered all the
data we had available.

00:34:07.570 --> 00:34:10.030
And first of all, to calibrate
the landscape of immunity

00:34:10.030 --> 00:34:13.270
we pulled together the
vaccination coverage surveys

00:34:13.270 --> 00:34:16.880
that had been done in
Pakistan over previous years.

00:34:16.880 --> 00:34:19.480
And it's quite a luxury having
vaccination coverage surveys

00:34:19.480 --> 00:34:21.820
because this doesn't exist
for many of the settings

00:34:21.820 --> 00:34:24.880
where measles is a concern.

00:34:24.880 --> 00:34:27.260
We put this together with
births and we put this together

00:34:27.260 --> 00:34:30.710
with our best guess of what the
history of infection had been.

00:34:30.710 --> 00:34:32.389
And this is actually
a reasonable thing

00:34:32.389 --> 00:34:35.219
to do because in the
era pre-vaccination

00:34:35.219 --> 00:34:38.090
it's reasonable to assume
that everybody got measles.

00:34:38.090 --> 00:34:40.340
There's this great quotation,
measles is like love,

00:34:40.340 --> 00:34:41.690
everybody gets it.

00:34:41.690 --> 00:34:45.364
And it was definitely
true back in the day.

00:34:45.364 --> 00:34:47.030
So we built a picture
of what we thought

00:34:47.030 --> 00:34:48.830
the landscape of immunity was.

00:34:48.830 --> 00:34:52.760
And then to put this
together with human mobility,

00:34:52.760 --> 00:34:57.350
we leveraged a source of data
that Caroline really pioneered,

00:34:57.350 --> 00:34:59.090
which is using mobile
phone call data

00:34:59.090 --> 00:35:01.700
records to capture
how people are

00:35:01.700 --> 00:35:03.770
moving across the landscape.

00:35:03.770 --> 00:35:06.020
And the way this works
is that every time you

00:35:06.020 --> 00:35:08.270
make a call, the
tower that you're

00:35:08.270 --> 00:35:10.850
closest to routes that call.

00:35:10.850 --> 00:35:12.770
So if we know where
the towers are and we

00:35:12.770 --> 00:35:15.260
have a record of the
calls, we can figure out

00:35:15.260 --> 00:35:18.710
these large scale
fluxes of population.

00:35:18.710 --> 00:35:21.770
And this data comes with
no other information.

00:35:21.770 --> 00:35:24.710
We just know where people are
and where they've moved to.

00:35:24.710 --> 00:35:25.970
We don't know their age.

00:35:25.970 --> 00:35:27.860
We don't know the
vaccination status.

00:35:27.860 --> 00:35:32.110
What we have is
fluxes of mobility.

00:35:32.110 --> 00:35:33.900
So to evaluate our
ability to predict,

00:35:33.900 --> 00:35:37.350
we're also going to need
information on measles itself.

00:35:37.350 --> 00:35:40.060
And so we had two
sources of data here.

00:35:40.060 --> 00:35:43.050
One was province
scale case reports.

00:35:43.050 --> 00:35:45.840
So over the time scale
from September 2012

00:35:45.840 --> 00:35:51.700
on the left going forward to
September 2013 on the right,

00:35:51.700 --> 00:35:53.960
there were records
of numbers of cases

00:35:53.960 --> 00:35:57.520
in each of the provinces of
Pakistan shown by the colors.

00:35:57.520 --> 00:36:00.200
So we compiled that data.

00:36:00.200 --> 00:36:01.310
It's not perfect, right?

00:36:01.310 --> 00:36:02.934
If you're interested
in human mobility,

00:36:02.934 --> 00:36:05.120
Pakistan is rather large
and provinces is rather

00:36:05.120 --> 00:36:08.120
a large scale to be
thinking about this problem.

00:36:08.120 --> 00:36:10.004
So we also pulled in
another source of data.

00:36:10.004 --> 00:36:12.170
And this was a different
source of information which

00:36:12.170 --> 00:36:16.010
was district levels alert data.

00:36:16.010 --> 00:36:19.460
So when local health officials
of a particular district

00:36:19.460 --> 00:36:22.662
thought a measles
outbreak was kicking off,

00:36:22.662 --> 00:36:24.620
that data was sent up to
the Ministry of Health

00:36:24.620 --> 00:36:26.030
and was available to us.

00:36:26.030 --> 00:36:27.620
It's not actually instance data.

00:36:27.620 --> 00:36:29.600
We don't know the total number
of cases that were there.

00:36:29.600 --> 00:36:31.516
They might just have
flagged up that something

00:36:31.516 --> 00:36:33.190
was about to happen.

00:36:33.190 --> 00:36:37.340
OK, so how am I going to see
if I can predict this data?

00:36:37.340 --> 00:36:39.370
Well, what I'm going
to do is build a model

00:36:39.370 --> 00:36:40.660
of what Pakistan looks like.

00:36:40.660 --> 00:36:42.820
And this is a very crude
cartoon, obviously,

00:36:42.820 --> 00:36:44.780
for feasibility.

00:36:44.780 --> 00:36:47.650
If every one of the points
is a different district, what

00:36:47.650 --> 00:36:49.870
the mobile phone data
gives me is a sense

00:36:49.870 --> 00:36:51.640
of the fluxes of
individuals between all

00:36:51.640 --> 00:36:52.841
these different points.

00:36:52.841 --> 00:36:54.340
So there might be
strong connections

00:36:54.340 --> 00:36:56.215
between some districts
and weaker connections

00:36:56.215 --> 00:36:57.780
between others.

00:36:57.780 --> 00:37:00.520
For every one of these districts
I also have a sense of what

00:37:00.520 --> 00:37:04.100
proportion of the population
is immune to measles and what

00:37:04.100 --> 00:37:04.600
isn't.

00:37:04.600 --> 00:37:08.140
And that's going to matter
for the pathogen spread.

00:37:08.140 --> 00:37:11.530
So I have my sense of how
the world works based on all

00:37:11.530 --> 00:37:13.570
the big data that I have.

00:37:13.570 --> 00:37:16.117
And then what I'm going to
do is initiate an outbreak

00:37:16.117 --> 00:37:18.700
in the setting where I know that
the outbreak kicked off based

00:37:18.700 --> 00:37:21.454
on the district alert data.

00:37:21.454 --> 00:37:22.870
And I'm going to
run a simulation.

00:37:22.870 --> 00:37:25.720
And this works essentially by
saying, the outbreak begins.

00:37:25.720 --> 00:37:27.370
It might have moved,
you know, if this

00:37:27.370 --> 00:37:29.710
was the district that
was most connected it

00:37:29.710 --> 00:37:31.960
might have moved here next.

00:37:31.960 --> 00:37:34.060
The outbreak continues in
the two first districts.

00:37:34.060 --> 00:37:37.570
It might move to a
third, and so on.

00:37:37.570 --> 00:37:41.249
So over time, I'm going to
have a full simulation of what

00:37:41.249 --> 00:37:42.790
the outbreak looked
like in every one

00:37:42.790 --> 00:37:44.950
of the districts of Pakistan.

00:37:44.950 --> 00:37:47.170
And importantly, every
time I rerun this you

00:37:47.170 --> 00:37:49.000
might get a slightly
different picture

00:37:49.000 --> 00:37:51.670
because I'm assuming that
chance is going to play a role.

00:37:51.670 --> 00:37:54.940
That some routes are going
to be fairly similarly

00:37:54.940 --> 00:37:57.010
important at different
times, and so we're

00:37:57.010 --> 00:37:59.410
flipping a coin to figure
out which one predominates.

00:37:59.410 --> 00:38:02.915
So every simulation might end up
looking a little bit different.

00:38:02.915 --> 00:38:04.540
But overall, they
look a bit like this.

00:38:04.540 --> 00:38:06.550
So this is simulated
trajectories

00:38:06.550 --> 00:38:10.060
across all districts in Pakistan
based on the mobile phone

00:38:10.060 --> 00:38:12.760
data and the landscape
of immunity data.

00:38:12.760 --> 00:38:15.500
The x-axis is time in by
weeks over the time course

00:38:15.500 --> 00:38:17.130
we were focused on.

00:38:17.130 --> 00:38:20.922
And the y-axis is the
number of cases we obtained.

00:38:20.922 --> 00:38:22.630
So we need a way to
evaluate whether this

00:38:22.630 --> 00:38:23.880
is any good or not, obviously.

00:38:23.880 --> 00:38:27.290
And so for that, we go back
to our original district alert

00:38:27.290 --> 00:38:27.790
data.

00:38:27.790 --> 00:38:31.930
The province level data is just
too coarse to do much with.

00:38:31.930 --> 00:38:35.180
And we chose to focus
on the question of,

00:38:35.180 --> 00:38:38.020
could we anticipate,
could we predict

00:38:38.020 --> 00:38:40.540
how many districts would
occur after a certain point

00:38:40.540 --> 00:38:42.370
in the future?

00:38:42.370 --> 00:38:44.680
Because in that case,
we could rush out there.

00:38:44.680 --> 00:38:46.180
We could start
preparing campaigns,

00:38:46.180 --> 00:38:48.650
we could maybe get
ahead of the wave

00:38:48.650 --> 00:38:53.410
and that would be a considerable
public health benefit.

00:38:53.410 --> 00:38:57.220
So on this plot, what we have is
time and by weeks on the x-axis

00:38:57.220 --> 00:38:58.600
into the future.

00:38:58.600 --> 00:39:00.850
And on the y-axis is the
proportion of districts

00:39:00.850 --> 00:39:04.030
that we accurately predict to
have happened after the time

00:39:04.030 --> 00:39:06.460
point on the x-axis.

00:39:06.460 --> 00:39:09.730
So at the start of the outbreak,
100% of districts happening

00:39:09.730 --> 00:39:11.790
in the future, we do quite well.

00:39:11.790 --> 00:39:14.360
That's not too impressive.

00:39:14.360 --> 00:39:16.600
And then the
proportion predicted

00:39:16.600 --> 00:39:19.336
to happen in the
future falls off.

00:39:19.336 --> 00:39:23.660
And by about 10 by week,
so about five months,

00:39:23.660 --> 00:39:25.960
we're doing as well
as a coin flip.

00:39:25.960 --> 00:39:27.670
So we're doing 50%.

00:39:27.670 --> 00:39:30.400
And after that, our
predictions get even worse.

00:39:30.400 --> 00:39:32.020
Because we have a
model, and the model

00:39:32.020 --> 00:39:36.490
is less good than just saying,
stuff might happen by chance.

00:39:36.490 --> 00:39:38.560
So, is it helpful?

00:39:38.560 --> 00:39:40.590
It's been estimated
during measles outbreaks

00:39:40.590 --> 00:39:43.980
in Malawi that it takes about
two to three months to get

00:39:43.980 --> 00:39:45.481
a campaign up and running.

00:39:45.481 --> 00:39:46.980
So we're buying a
little bit of time

00:39:46.980 --> 00:39:49.620
there, potentially
on that scale.

00:39:49.620 --> 00:39:51.430
But we're not doing great.

00:39:51.430 --> 00:39:55.950
It's important to think about
why we aren't doing great.

00:39:55.950 --> 00:39:59.580
And in this context, it's
important to remember

00:39:59.580 --> 00:40:03.660
that every one of
our data sources

00:40:03.660 --> 00:40:05.400
has uncertainties in it.

00:40:05.400 --> 00:40:08.220
So the vaccination data might
have reporting biases in it.

00:40:08.220 --> 00:40:10.590
We might only be
finding the children

00:40:10.590 --> 00:40:13.170
to report on coverage
who had been vaccinated

00:40:13.170 --> 00:40:15.640
because the ones who aren't
vaccinated, by definition,

00:40:15.640 --> 00:40:18.120
are probably hard to find.

00:40:18.120 --> 00:40:20.010
We might have a large
population, therefore,

00:40:20.010 --> 00:40:21.199
of missed children.

00:40:21.199 --> 00:40:22.740
So our vaccination
coverage estimates

00:40:22.740 --> 00:40:25.240
will be really optimistic.

00:40:25.240 --> 00:40:27.490
Mobility data, mobile phone
data is really amazing

00:40:27.490 --> 00:40:28.990
and gives you this
incredible window

00:40:28.990 --> 00:40:31.429
into how people are moving
around the landscape.

00:40:31.429 --> 00:40:33.220
We don't know if it's
relevant to children.

00:40:33.220 --> 00:40:35.511
We don't know if it's relevant
to transmission from one

00:40:35.511 --> 00:40:37.540
individual to the next.

00:40:37.540 --> 00:40:40.690
There's a quite specific biology
underlying measles transmission

00:40:40.690 --> 00:40:43.570
and these big fluxes
might not capture it.

00:40:43.570 --> 00:40:44.710
And then the case data.

00:40:44.710 --> 00:40:47.830
It's true everywhere in the
world, even and outbreak

00:40:47.830 --> 00:40:49.840
in Holland in 2007
it was estimated

00:40:49.840 --> 00:40:53.470
that 10% of measles
cases were reported.

00:40:53.470 --> 00:40:55.270
Nobody reported measles cases.

00:40:55.270 --> 00:40:57.876
So that data is
also fairly erratic.

00:40:57.876 --> 00:40:59.500
And I think this
comes back to a thread

00:40:59.500 --> 00:41:01.900
that Caroline alluded
to in the beginning.

00:41:01.900 --> 00:41:05.020
To make any progress
around really leveraging

00:41:05.020 --> 00:41:09.250
these unique and powerful
novel sources of information

00:41:09.250 --> 00:41:13.570
requires really strengthening
existing sources of information

00:41:13.570 --> 00:41:17.090
and really basic epidemiology,
case reports, vaccination

00:41:17.090 --> 00:41:17.590
coverage.

00:41:17.590 --> 00:41:20.215
No one ever seems to write down
what fraction of the population

00:41:20.215 --> 00:41:21.220
they vaccinated.

00:41:21.220 --> 00:41:22.750
Possibly because they have
more important things to do,

00:41:22.750 --> 00:41:24.791
like vaccinate children,
but it would be helpful.

00:41:27.550 --> 00:41:29.490
So one of the things
we've been thinking about

00:41:29.490 --> 00:41:32.490
as we move forwards
in this space

00:41:32.490 --> 00:41:36.604
is I told you I need two pieces
to really try and predict

00:41:36.604 --> 00:41:38.520
where and when an outbreak
is going to happen.

00:41:38.520 --> 00:41:40.200
And even for measles,
which is perhaps

00:41:40.200 --> 00:41:43.530
one of the world's simplest and
best understood of pathogens,

00:41:43.530 --> 00:41:46.162
it's really hard.

00:41:46.162 --> 00:41:48.370
And we ended up thinking
about, is there another way?

00:41:48.370 --> 00:41:49.786
Is there another
approach we could

00:41:49.786 --> 00:41:53.170
take to refining
our understanding

00:41:53.170 --> 00:41:56.021
of the landscape of immunity?

00:41:56.021 --> 00:41:57.520
And really, we
started from the fact

00:41:57.520 --> 00:41:59.770
that this is the central
process in epidemiology.

00:41:59.770 --> 00:42:02.100
I told you, individuals
start off susceptible,

00:42:02.100 --> 00:42:05.170
that's the S. They become
infected if they encounter

00:42:05.170 --> 00:42:06.450
an infected person.

00:42:06.450 --> 00:42:08.780
That's the I. And
then they recover.

00:42:08.780 --> 00:42:11.680
And just about every
piece of modeling

00:42:11.680 --> 00:42:13.960
around infectious
diseases has some variant

00:42:13.960 --> 00:42:16.920
of this basic schematic in it.

00:42:16.920 --> 00:42:19.320
Yet all we ever see when
we're trying to build

00:42:19.320 --> 00:42:23.330
these forecasts is cases.

00:42:23.330 --> 00:42:26.014
The susceptibles and the
recovereds are invisible to us.

00:42:28.800 --> 00:42:31.050
And we can infer who's
susceptible and who isn't.

00:42:31.050 --> 00:42:32.580
That's what I did here.

00:42:32.580 --> 00:42:35.490
I pulled together information on
births and vaccinations to try

00:42:35.490 --> 00:42:37.990
and figure out who could
have got the infection,

00:42:37.990 --> 00:42:40.280
who was protected,
and who wasn't.

00:42:40.280 --> 00:42:42.270
And in measles--
this is an example

00:42:42.270 --> 00:42:45.060
of pre-vaccination measles
in England and Wales.

00:42:45.060 --> 00:42:46.440
It's very straightforward.

00:42:46.440 --> 00:42:48.480
The number of
susceptibles in two weeks

00:42:48.480 --> 00:42:50.580
time is the number
of susceptibles now

00:42:50.580 --> 00:42:53.100
plus new births minus
whoever got infected.

00:42:53.100 --> 00:42:55.600
So you just iterate it forwards
and you have your trajectory

00:42:55.600 --> 00:42:57.932
of susceptibles.

00:42:57.932 --> 00:43:00.390
Almost everywhere in the world
would be a lot like Pakistan

00:43:00.390 --> 00:43:03.930
where the case data was shaky,
the vaccination coverage data

00:43:03.930 --> 00:43:04.929
was shaky.

00:43:04.929 --> 00:43:06.720
In fact, everywhere
now has measles vaccine

00:43:06.720 --> 00:43:09.280
so you have to account for it.

00:43:09.280 --> 00:43:12.130
But it turns out that there is
potentially another approach

00:43:12.130 --> 00:43:14.470
to getting at that.

00:43:14.470 --> 00:43:17.470
And that is that
serology can directly

00:43:17.470 --> 00:43:19.051
measure susceptibility.

00:43:19.051 --> 00:43:21.300
So this is where if I were
to go out into the audience

00:43:21.300 --> 00:43:25.080
and take your blood, which
would be very strange,

00:43:25.080 --> 00:43:30.010
I could evaluate whether you had
been vaccinated against measles

00:43:30.010 --> 00:43:31.030
or not.

00:43:31.030 --> 00:43:33.370
And I'm guessing that
everybody in this audience

00:43:33.370 --> 00:43:36.880
has an antibody titer that
is protective to measles.

00:43:36.880 --> 00:43:40.656
In my case, it's actually
because I was infected.

00:43:40.656 --> 00:43:42.280
But we can discuss
that with my mother.

00:43:45.312 --> 00:43:47.770
And you can do much more nuanced
really interesting things.

00:43:47.770 --> 00:43:50.590
So for example, I could
evaluate whether you'd

00:43:50.590 --> 00:43:53.530
been exposed to
particular flu strains,

00:43:53.530 --> 00:43:56.922
like Hong Kong 68 or Bangkok 71.

00:43:56.922 --> 00:43:59.380
Which tells me whether you were
in a part of the world that

00:43:59.380 --> 00:44:02.980
was connected to the
rest of the globe

00:44:02.980 --> 00:44:05.230
during these global pandemics.

00:44:05.230 --> 00:44:09.610
So it's an incredible window
onto the past of populations.

00:44:09.610 --> 00:44:12.430
And it's an incredible window
into predicting the future,

00:44:12.430 --> 00:44:15.160
and the likely
burden of infections.

00:44:15.160 --> 00:44:16.280
It allows us to project.

00:44:16.280 --> 00:44:20.110
It gives us a direct measure
of this landscape of immunity.

00:44:20.110 --> 00:44:22.750
And so with colleagues,
one of the things

00:44:22.750 --> 00:44:25.720
we're very excited
about moving forwards

00:44:25.720 --> 00:44:28.330
in considering big
data and the world

00:44:28.330 --> 00:44:31.240
of contagion and
epidemics is developing

00:44:31.240 --> 00:44:33.920
a global immunological
observatory.

00:44:33.920 --> 00:44:37.750
And our logic here is that
if you think about weather

00:44:37.750 --> 00:44:40.540
forecasting, we have
buoys distributed

00:44:40.540 --> 00:44:43.960
all over the seas of the
world to measure sea surface

00:44:43.960 --> 00:44:47.944
temperature to strengthen our
prediction of global climate.

00:44:47.944 --> 00:44:49.360
And yet we have
nothing equivalent

00:44:49.360 --> 00:44:51.520
for infectious diseases.

00:44:51.520 --> 00:44:55.630
But all of our blood is
this unbelievable sensor

00:44:55.630 --> 00:44:57.760
of all the things
we've been exposed to,

00:44:57.760 --> 00:45:00.310
all the things we've
been infected by.

00:45:00.310 --> 00:45:02.170
And the technology is
ramping up to a stage

00:45:02.170 --> 00:45:04.420
where you need smaller
and smaller samples

00:45:04.420 --> 00:45:06.160
and you can get more
and more resolution

00:45:06.160 --> 00:45:09.630
across even more pathogens.

00:45:09.630 --> 00:45:12.850
It would give you the
prospects of anticipating

00:45:12.850 --> 00:45:14.620
hidden epidemics or
at least understanding

00:45:14.620 --> 00:45:17.860
when they were occurring long
before perhaps cases blipped up

00:45:17.860 --> 00:45:18.460
on the radio.

00:45:22.310 --> 00:45:24.500
You might be thinking,
well, that's not,

00:45:24.500 --> 00:45:26.960
I mean, how are we
going to store that?

00:45:26.960 --> 00:45:28.190
What are the ethics of it?

00:45:28.190 --> 00:45:29.231
And it's absolutely true.

00:45:29.231 --> 00:45:31.670
There's a huge amount of
both ethical and logistical

00:45:31.670 --> 00:45:33.930
considerations that
have to come through.

00:45:33.930 --> 00:45:36.290
But I think the prospects
are such that there are so

00:45:36.290 --> 00:45:38.600
many ways in which you could
use convenience samples,

00:45:38.600 --> 00:45:40.077
if you think about blood banks.

00:45:40.077 --> 00:45:41.660
We could be using
blood banks to think

00:45:41.660 --> 00:45:44.810
about what the world's kind of
epidemiological and contagion

00:45:44.810 --> 00:45:46.520
risks are.

00:45:46.520 --> 00:45:50.090
There are all sorts
of carefully designed

00:45:50.090 --> 00:45:51.680
nationally
representative surveys

00:45:51.680 --> 00:45:53.720
that could add a
biological sample to it.

00:45:53.720 --> 00:45:55.220
And there's even
the prospect of not

00:45:55.220 --> 00:45:58.290
needing to use blood because
it's really hard to get blood,

00:45:58.290 --> 00:46:01.250
but using saliva for
some of these techniques

00:46:01.250 --> 00:46:04.032
with many of the new
technological innovations,

00:46:04.032 --> 00:46:05.990
many of which are actually
happening at Harvard

00:46:05.990 --> 00:46:08.060
that would allow us to do this.

00:46:08.060 --> 00:46:10.010
So that's all I have.

00:46:10.010 --> 00:46:15.200
And I did all of this with
Caroline, Andy Tatem, and other

00:46:15.200 --> 00:46:16.240
[INAUDIBLE].

00:46:16.240 --> 00:46:17.300
Thank you very much.

00:46:17.300 --> 00:46:20.660
[APPLAUSE]

00:46:26.420 --> 00:46:28.490
- Thank you, Jess.

00:46:28.490 --> 00:46:33.080
So our final speaker for today's
panel is going to move from--

00:46:33.080 --> 00:46:37.310
we've been to global threats,
and national vaccination

00:46:37.310 --> 00:46:38.720
programs, and serology.

00:46:38.720 --> 00:46:42.290
Ami Bhatt from Stanford
is going to talk

00:46:42.290 --> 00:46:47.270
now about a more personal scale,
thinking about the microbiome

00:46:47.270 --> 00:46:49.820
and how our
bacterial communities

00:46:49.820 --> 00:46:53.630
and viral communities interact
to create susceptibility

00:46:53.630 --> 00:46:54.140
to disease.

00:46:54.140 --> 00:46:56.900
And what it can teach us about
the development of new drugs

00:46:56.900 --> 00:46:59.240
and approaches to
make people healthy.

00:47:04.370 --> 00:47:06.200
- All right, so
thank you very much.

00:47:06.200 --> 00:47:08.220
What a pleasure to be
a part of this event

00:47:08.220 --> 00:47:10.470
and to be a part of this panel.

00:47:10.470 --> 00:47:13.070
So I'm going to speak
for the microbes today.

00:47:13.070 --> 00:47:15.080
And I'm going to think
about epidemics with you

00:47:15.080 --> 00:47:17.540
all through the lens
of the microbiome.

00:47:17.540 --> 00:47:19.940
And whether we like it or
not, a huge wave of data

00:47:19.940 --> 00:47:22.520
are coming at us and we're
just at the beginning

00:47:22.520 --> 00:47:26.510
of trying to build tools to
understand these microbes,

00:47:26.510 --> 00:47:31.250
to enumerate these microbes, and
to figure out how they change

00:47:31.250 --> 00:47:34.370
over time and space.

00:47:34.370 --> 00:47:36.950
So I'm going to start out
by helping you get to know

00:47:36.950 --> 00:47:39.660
your trillions of neighbors.

00:47:39.660 --> 00:47:42.120
I'll try to convince you
that context matters.

00:47:42.120 --> 00:47:45.100
And I'll try to give you a sense
of the perils of a simplified

00:47:45.100 --> 00:47:47.340
microbiome.

00:47:47.340 --> 00:47:49.020
I'll scare you a little bit.

00:47:49.020 --> 00:47:52.520
Our microbiome are under siege.

00:47:52.520 --> 00:47:55.390
And I'll remind you that
while we talk about pathogens

00:47:55.390 --> 00:47:58.550
and microorganisms as though
they're stagnant organisms,

00:47:58.550 --> 00:48:01.990
they're alive and
they're changing.

00:48:01.990 --> 00:48:04.570
I'll end by giving you
a very simple example

00:48:04.570 --> 00:48:09.130
of microbial evolution
on a clinical time scale.

00:48:09.130 --> 00:48:13.000
So number one, getting to know
your trillions of neighbors.

00:48:13.000 --> 00:48:15.990
We are one, but we are many.

00:48:15.990 --> 00:48:18.990
There are about 10 to 100
trillion microbes within each

00:48:18.990 --> 00:48:21.200
and every one of us.

00:48:21.200 --> 00:48:24.500
They make up about 3%
of our human body mass.

00:48:24.500 --> 00:48:29.560
We have 1 to 10 times as many
microbes as we do human cells.

00:48:29.560 --> 00:48:33.460
There are 10 to 100 times
many microbial genes

00:48:33.460 --> 00:48:35.500
as there are human genes.

00:48:35.500 --> 00:48:37.840
And of course, as you all
know, the largest number

00:48:37.840 --> 00:48:41.960
of microbes that we have
are in our GI tract.

00:48:41.960 --> 00:48:43.970
Over the course
of today's seminar

00:48:43.970 --> 00:48:47.060
we've heard a lot about
how microbes can be bad.

00:48:47.060 --> 00:48:49.770
And I'm not here to disagree.

00:48:49.770 --> 00:48:54.300
But sometimes they can
be good, or neutral.

00:48:54.300 --> 00:48:56.150
We know that we
exist or co-exist

00:48:56.150 --> 00:48:57.920
with these trillions
of microorganisms

00:48:57.920 --> 00:49:04.040
and that they are inexplicably
intertwined with ourselves.

00:49:04.040 --> 00:49:06.140
And so while many of us
will look at this picture

00:49:06.140 --> 00:49:09.510
and see the host or the
faces, when I look at this,

00:49:09.510 --> 00:49:10.880
I see the microbes.

00:49:10.880 --> 00:49:13.850
And what I understand is
that if the microbes change,

00:49:13.850 --> 00:49:16.006
well, perhaps we will as well.

00:49:16.006 --> 00:49:18.380
And so part of what motivates
me as a physician scientist

00:49:18.380 --> 00:49:21.140
is trying to understand
this interface so that we

00:49:21.140 --> 00:49:24.110
can manipulate host health
through manipulation

00:49:24.110 --> 00:49:26.230
of the microbiota.

00:49:26.230 --> 00:49:29.590
So I alluded to the fact that
microorganisms can be good.

00:49:29.590 --> 00:49:32.350
And to make this point, I'll
actually pull an example

00:49:32.350 --> 00:49:34.424
from the animal kingdom.

00:49:34.424 --> 00:49:36.840
I like elephants, which is
part of why I have this picture

00:49:36.840 --> 00:49:37.650
here.

00:49:37.650 --> 00:49:40.050
But it turns out that this
is also an excellent example

00:49:40.050 --> 00:49:42.450
of why microorganisms are good.

00:49:42.450 --> 00:49:45.210
So elephants are one
of many organisms

00:49:45.210 --> 00:49:47.370
that actually eat poop.

00:49:47.370 --> 00:49:49.500
They don't eat poop
throughout their lifetime,

00:49:49.500 --> 00:49:51.490
they only do it when
they're children.

00:49:51.490 --> 00:49:56.070
And if babies do not eat stool
from adults from the herd,

00:49:56.070 --> 00:49:58.240
they actually have
a runting problem,

00:49:58.240 --> 00:50:00.180
which means that they
don't grow properly.

00:50:00.180 --> 00:50:04.080
The microorganisms that they
acquire through adult feces

00:50:04.080 --> 00:50:06.270
actually help them
to extract energy

00:50:06.270 --> 00:50:08.110
from their food optimally.

00:50:08.110 --> 00:50:09.600
So this is an
excellent example I

00:50:09.600 --> 00:50:14.670
think from the natural world
about microbial good guys.

00:50:14.670 --> 00:50:19.140
When we think about microbiome
sciences and the little tidbits

00:50:19.140 --> 00:50:21.810
that I gave you earlier, a
lot of how we've enumerated

00:50:21.810 --> 00:50:24.900
understood the microbiome
has relied upon techniques

00:50:24.900 --> 00:50:26.210
for enumeration.

00:50:26.210 --> 00:50:28.020
And while light
microscopy was probably

00:50:28.020 --> 00:50:29.760
the first method
that was successfully

00:50:29.760 --> 00:50:31.800
applied to enumerate
microorganisms

00:50:31.800 --> 00:50:35.190
that were visible, there
are other methods as well.

00:50:35.190 --> 00:50:37.060
And a vast majority
of these methods

00:50:37.060 --> 00:50:40.490
now rely upon DNA
or RNA sequencing.

00:50:40.490 --> 00:50:42.150
And so Professor
Happi earlier today

00:50:42.150 --> 00:50:46.290
talked about beautiful work
using DNA and RNA sequencing

00:50:46.290 --> 00:50:49.590
to enumerate microorganisms,
in that case viruses,

00:50:49.590 --> 00:50:51.840
and to understand not
only whether or not

00:50:51.840 --> 00:50:55.120
they exist within a human,
but how they change over time.

00:50:55.120 --> 00:50:56.730
And so the fundamental
basis of most

00:50:56.730 --> 00:50:58.770
of the experiments
that I'll describe

00:50:58.770 --> 00:51:02.070
is taking a sample,
usually a mixed sample,

00:51:02.070 --> 00:51:05.580
sequencing it, generating these
lists of A's, and T's, and G's,

00:51:05.580 --> 00:51:08.160
and C's, and then
trying to infer

00:51:08.160 --> 00:51:12.790
from that information what
microorganisms are present.

00:51:12.790 --> 00:51:16.360
Put more simplistically,
my job is to collect stool,

00:51:16.360 --> 00:51:20.110
to extract nucleic acids, and
to ask simple questions like,

00:51:20.110 --> 00:51:20.920
who's there?

00:51:20.920 --> 00:51:21.880
What are they doing?

00:51:21.880 --> 00:51:23.440
And what do they make?

00:51:23.440 --> 00:51:25.030
In order to do so,
obviously we're

00:51:25.030 --> 00:51:28.070
generating gigabytes and
now terabytes of data.

00:51:28.070 --> 00:51:30.550
And so we require high
throughput computational

00:51:30.550 --> 00:51:32.170
pipelines to actually
achieve this.

00:51:34.820 --> 00:51:37.660
So next, we're going
to talk about context.

00:51:37.660 --> 00:51:40.210
And I'm going to try to convince
you that context matters,

00:51:40.210 --> 00:51:42.340
and that having a
simplified microbiome

00:51:42.340 --> 00:51:44.050
comes with its problems.

00:51:44.050 --> 00:51:47.180
So for that, I was really happy
to see that I had this orange.

00:51:47.180 --> 00:51:48.640
I got this orange for my lunch.

00:51:48.640 --> 00:51:50.800
I'll eat it at the break.

00:51:50.800 --> 00:51:52.000
You know, this is an orange.

00:51:52.000 --> 00:51:55.240
This is probably not
very scary to any of you.

00:51:55.240 --> 00:51:58.750
I presume you do not
find it threatening.

00:51:58.750 --> 00:52:03.970
You probably also do not
find this orange threatening.

00:52:03.970 --> 00:52:08.090
I think almost all of
you have seen this movie.

00:52:08.090 --> 00:52:09.250
This is from The Godfather.

00:52:09.250 --> 00:52:12.100
For those of you who haven't
seen The Godfather, you should.

00:52:12.100 --> 00:52:14.260
These are an excellent
series of movies.

00:52:14.260 --> 00:52:16.390
But on a more serious
note, in The Godfather

00:52:16.390 --> 00:52:19.750
you may notice that every time
there is an orange in a scene,

00:52:19.750 --> 00:52:22.510
it actually portends bad things.

00:52:22.510 --> 00:52:25.760
And usually the person
engaged with the orange dies.

00:52:25.760 --> 00:52:29.170
Sorry, spoiler alert.

00:52:29.170 --> 00:52:33.910
So, you know, these
oranges, not so bad.

00:52:33.910 --> 00:52:37.250
Those oranges, quite worrisome.

00:52:37.250 --> 00:52:40.990
And so an orange, is not an
orange, is not an orange.

00:52:40.990 --> 00:52:44.980
Likewise, microbes
are not always

00:52:44.980 --> 00:52:47.960
pathogenic in all circumstances.

00:52:47.960 --> 00:52:50.320
And so the context
in which you view

00:52:50.320 --> 00:52:53.200
those microbes and the context
in which they exist actually

00:52:53.200 --> 00:52:56.900
strongly affects their function.

00:52:56.900 --> 00:53:00.410
So we'll turn now to the perils
of the simplified microbiome

00:53:00.410 --> 00:53:05.040
and think about
context in that way.

00:53:05.040 --> 00:53:06.830
So here are two microbiomes.

00:53:06.830 --> 00:53:09.570
The one on the left is
a complex microbiome.

00:53:09.570 --> 00:53:11.810
This is what, for example
your stool microbial

00:53:11.810 --> 00:53:13.160
might look like.

00:53:13.160 --> 00:53:15.500
The one on the right is,
obviously, very simplified.

00:53:15.500 --> 00:53:20.330
All you see is these Good
and Plenty looking rods.

00:53:20.330 --> 00:53:23.810
It turns out this exists
in clinical medicine.

00:53:23.810 --> 00:53:26.510
So an example of how this
exists in clinical medicine

00:53:26.510 --> 00:53:28.700
is in the setting of C. diff.

00:53:28.700 --> 00:53:31.130
Many of you have heard of C.
diff, clostridium difficile.

00:53:31.130 --> 00:53:34.250
Now actually, it's called
pepto clostridium difficile.

00:53:34.250 --> 00:53:36.890
Is an organism that
is an opportunist.

00:53:36.890 --> 00:53:42.110
And typically, it exists,
colonizes many healthy people.

00:53:42.110 --> 00:53:44.886
We have a few hundred people
in here, about 5% of us

00:53:44.886 --> 00:53:46.010
are colonized with C. diff.

00:53:46.010 --> 00:53:48.230
It doesn't cause any problems.

00:53:48.230 --> 00:53:50.990
However, in the setting of
a simplified microbiomes

00:53:50.990 --> 00:53:55.600
when you don't have a healthy
context, it causes disease.

00:53:55.600 --> 00:53:58.100
So this is an example
of an opportunist

00:53:58.100 --> 00:54:01.350
that is pathogenic only
in a given context.

00:54:01.350 --> 00:54:03.800
And so while we can look at
pathogens, and infectious,

00:54:03.800 --> 00:54:06.566
disease, and epidemics
and contagions

00:54:06.566 --> 00:54:07.940
through the lens
of the pathogen,

00:54:07.940 --> 00:54:10.040
we can also think about
it from the standpoint

00:54:10.040 --> 00:54:14.270
of those who are susceptible,
as just pointed out.

00:54:14.270 --> 00:54:16.790
Now, many of you know of the
most successful treatments

00:54:16.790 --> 00:54:20.000
for C. diff is actually
not antibiotics,

00:54:20.000 --> 00:54:22.950
but fecal microbiota
transplantation.

00:54:22.950 --> 00:54:25.970
This happens to be my
favorite picture of FMT which

00:54:25.970 --> 00:54:29.090
shows you connecting two
people's colons, which

00:54:29.090 --> 00:54:30.080
we obviously do not do.

00:54:33.490 --> 00:54:35.710
Over on the right
this is like probably

00:54:35.710 --> 00:54:37.780
not right after lunch
picture, but this

00:54:37.780 --> 00:54:40.560
is an example of a crapsule.

00:54:40.560 --> 00:54:41.230
This is--

00:54:41.230 --> 00:54:44.040
[LAUGHTER]

00:54:44.040 --> 00:54:46.780
This is just from across
the river over at MGH,

00:54:46.780 --> 00:54:48.700
A colleague of
mine, Libby Hohmann,

00:54:48.700 --> 00:54:50.380
generates these capsules.

00:54:50.380 --> 00:54:53.120
And actually, if you take
15 of those pills one day,

00:54:53.120 --> 00:54:54.940
15 pills the next
day you can actually

00:54:54.940 --> 00:54:58.199
have a very high rate of
cure of your C. difficile.

00:54:58.199 --> 00:54:59.740
In part, because
what you're doing is

00:54:59.740 --> 00:55:03.520
you're giving a healthy
microbiome context back

00:55:03.520 --> 00:55:06.100
to an individual who has
a simplified microbiome.

00:55:06.100 --> 00:55:08.990
How cool is that?

00:55:08.990 --> 00:55:13.072
Now, of course, our
microbes are under siege.

00:55:13.072 --> 00:55:14.030
I'm worried about them.

00:55:14.030 --> 00:55:15.950
I know you guys did
a good job of going

00:55:15.950 --> 00:55:19.400
and having lunch and taking
care of your microbes.

00:55:19.400 --> 00:55:23.510
But many have argued
that industrialization

00:55:23.510 --> 00:55:27.530
increases exposure to agents
that change our microbiome.

00:55:27.530 --> 00:55:29.900
So when you reflect upon
your daily life, what

00:55:29.900 --> 00:55:31.649
are the things that
we're doing that might

00:55:31.649 --> 00:55:32.930
simplify our microbiome?

00:55:32.930 --> 00:55:36.770
Well, if we look at humans
throughout evolutionary time,

00:55:36.770 --> 00:55:39.020
early on in the
hunter gatherer days

00:55:39.020 --> 00:55:42.270
the main thing that affected
our microbiome was our diet.

00:55:42.270 --> 00:55:45.050
Our diet, and occasional
exposure to pathogens that

00:55:45.050 --> 00:55:47.270
caused terrible
diarrhea and essentially

00:55:47.270 --> 00:55:49.550
kind of a clean out.

00:55:49.550 --> 00:55:53.090
As we went to a more
agricultural sort of setting,

00:55:53.090 --> 00:55:55.490
diet again was a major effector.

00:55:55.490 --> 00:55:57.380
As we became more and
more industrialized,

00:55:57.380 --> 00:55:59.930
heavy metals and
arsenic introduced

00:55:59.930 --> 00:56:02.070
were introduced into
our environment.

00:56:02.070 --> 00:56:04.850
And finally, in the modern day
adding onto those heavy metals

00:56:04.850 --> 00:56:07.190
and arsenic, we also
had broad scale exposure

00:56:07.190 --> 00:56:10.100
to antiseptics and antibiotics.

00:56:10.100 --> 00:56:12.099
So by a show of
hands, how many of you

00:56:12.099 --> 00:56:14.390
think you might have been
exposed to antibiotics today?

00:56:18.890 --> 00:56:22.600
I'm going to argue
that it's everyone.

00:56:22.600 --> 00:56:26.260
So this compound over on
the left is triclosan.

00:56:26.260 --> 00:56:29.200
Triclosan is a
common antiseptic.

00:56:29.200 --> 00:56:32.470
It actually was originally
developed in the 1960s

00:56:32.470 --> 00:56:34.210
as a surgical anesthetic.

00:56:34.210 --> 00:56:35.680
It's a very simple molecule.

00:56:35.680 --> 00:56:37.430
And for those of you
who aren't chemists,

00:56:37.430 --> 00:56:39.370
anytime you see a simple
molecule you can look

00:56:39.370 --> 00:56:41.270
smart at a cocktail
party by saying,

00:56:41.270 --> 00:56:43.480
I bet somebody synthesized that.

00:56:43.480 --> 00:56:45.620
Because when nature
synthesizes molecules

00:56:45.620 --> 00:56:47.560
they're awfully complex.

00:56:47.560 --> 00:56:49.810
So this is a synthesized
antimicrobial.

00:56:49.810 --> 00:56:51.460
It's very broad spectrum.

00:56:51.460 --> 00:56:54.400
And it's in thousands
of consumer products.

00:56:54.400 --> 00:56:56.760
Now, you may know
that the FDA banned

00:56:56.760 --> 00:57:00.820
triclosan and several
related compounds in 2016.

00:57:00.820 --> 00:57:02.630
That ban just went into effect.

00:57:02.630 --> 00:57:05.410
So you won't see
anti-microbial hand soaps

00:57:05.410 --> 00:57:07.570
on your shelves for example.

00:57:07.570 --> 00:57:10.120
Now, while it was banned
in certain household wash

00:57:10.120 --> 00:57:12.999
products, it's still
present in lots of things.

00:57:12.999 --> 00:57:15.040
And I would guess that
even the chairs that we're

00:57:15.040 --> 00:57:17.410
sitting on today have
antimicrobials that

00:57:17.410 --> 00:57:20.650
are impregnated into the cloth.

00:57:20.650 --> 00:57:23.200
So Jessica Roboto, a talented
graduate student in my lab,

00:57:23.200 --> 00:57:24.340
decided to study this.

00:57:24.340 --> 00:57:26.260
And we collaborated
with an epidemiologist

00:57:26.260 --> 00:57:28.450
named Julie
Parsonnet at Stanford

00:57:28.450 --> 00:57:30.970
to evaluate the
impacts of triclosan

00:57:30.970 --> 00:57:34.180
on a cohort of mothers
and their babies.

00:57:34.180 --> 00:57:36.880
To make a long story short,
this is a complicated graph.

00:57:36.880 --> 00:57:39.580
But suffice it to say
that each dot represents

00:57:39.580 --> 00:57:41.050
a bacterial taxon.

00:57:41.050 --> 00:57:44.980
So a community of similar
types of microbes.

00:57:44.980 --> 00:57:47.660
If you have dots to the
right of the center line,

00:57:47.660 --> 00:57:49.960
these are microbes that
are enriched in households

00:57:49.960 --> 00:57:51.550
exposed to triclosan.

00:57:51.550 --> 00:57:53.560
If you see a dot
on the left, those

00:57:53.560 --> 00:57:56.200
are microbes that are
enriched in households

00:57:56.200 --> 00:57:58.480
exposed to the control agents.

00:57:58.480 --> 00:58:00.520
And what you can see
is in these adults

00:58:00.520 --> 00:58:02.590
they happen to be mothers.

00:58:02.590 --> 00:58:05.560
Over the course of time
we see an enrichment

00:58:05.560 --> 00:58:07.730
of these blue dots on the
right side of the graph.

00:58:07.730 --> 00:58:10.600
Which means these are organisms
that are enriched in households

00:58:10.600 --> 00:58:12.840
exposed to triclosan.

00:58:12.840 --> 00:58:15.150
Interestingly, in this
experiment what was done

00:58:15.150 --> 00:58:18.450
was between two and six
months these households were

00:58:18.450 --> 00:58:21.690
randomized to be
exposed to toothpaste

00:58:21.690 --> 00:58:24.250
that contain triclosan.

00:58:24.250 --> 00:58:26.710
Now, triclosan is not
banned from toothpaste.

00:58:26.710 --> 00:58:29.050
So while you won't see it
in antibacterial hand soap,

00:58:29.050 --> 00:58:31.090
you can walk down the
street to CVS and buy

00:58:31.090 --> 00:58:32.650
this particular toothpaste.

00:58:32.650 --> 00:58:36.680
And you can see that this is
actually having a broad effect.

00:58:36.680 --> 00:58:39.820
Triclosan is actually
the second most abundant

00:58:39.820 --> 00:58:42.610
human-made chemical in
waste water treatment plants

00:58:42.610 --> 00:58:44.930
and it abounds in
our groundwater.

00:58:44.930 --> 00:58:48.350
So whether we like it or not,
we're exposed to this compound.

00:58:48.350 --> 00:58:51.460
At least these data suggest
that these compounds

00:58:51.460 --> 00:58:53.683
are changing our microbiomes.

00:58:57.390 --> 00:58:59.064
You can look up this
in Jessica's paper

00:58:59.064 --> 00:59:00.730
that just came out
if you're interested.

00:59:00.730 --> 00:59:02.938
And I'm certainly happy to
answer any other questions

00:59:02.938 --> 00:59:05.590
you may have on it.

00:59:05.590 --> 00:59:09.160
But remember, not only are
our microbiomes under siege

00:59:09.160 --> 00:59:11.620
and our microbiomes
are changing,

00:59:11.620 --> 00:59:14.860
but our microbes themselves
are alive and changing.

00:59:14.860 --> 00:59:17.320
They adapt beautifully
to stressors.

00:59:17.320 --> 00:59:20.110
You saw evidence of how
they adapt over time

00:59:20.110 --> 00:59:23.762
and acquire mutations in
the setting of outbreaks.

00:59:23.762 --> 00:59:25.220
Fundamentally, for
those of you who

00:59:25.220 --> 00:59:28.610
are not molecular biologists,
or geneticists in the audience I

00:59:28.610 --> 00:59:31.220
though I would just break it
down into two main categories

00:59:31.220 --> 00:59:34.050
of ways microbes evolve.

00:59:34.050 --> 00:59:36.100
they acquire small mutations.

00:59:36.100 --> 00:59:38.820
And so in this case, the
highlighted red letters

00:59:38.820 --> 00:59:41.610
are changing to another letter.

00:59:41.610 --> 00:59:45.270
Or they can acquire
genes or gene fragments.

00:59:45.270 --> 00:59:49.660
And we usually call this
horizontal gene transfer.

00:59:49.660 --> 00:59:52.690
And so there are two main
ways bacteria can evolve.

00:59:52.690 --> 00:59:55.540
It turns out that we're pretty
good at measuring the way

00:59:55.540 --> 00:59:57.970
that organisms
evolve on the left.

00:59:57.970 --> 00:59:59.650
So we can measure
those mutations.

00:59:59.650 --> 01:00:03.040
Those are pretty easy
using current technologies.

01:00:03.040 --> 01:00:06.660
But measuring the thing on
the right has been difficult.

01:00:06.660 --> 01:00:08.400
And part of the
reason it's difficult

01:00:08.400 --> 01:00:11.370
is because when you have a
horizontal transferred segment,

01:00:11.370 --> 01:00:13.770
what it means is that what
you're seeing in this toy

01:00:13.770 --> 01:00:15.450
example actually occurs.

01:00:15.450 --> 01:00:18.000
Which is you have a repeated
segment, in this case labeled

01:00:18.000 --> 01:00:22.170
R, that exists both between
A and D in this case,

01:00:22.170 --> 01:00:25.600
as well as between
B and C. Now, this

01:00:25.600 --> 01:00:28.240
happens in nature, a
horizontal gene transfer.

01:00:28.240 --> 01:00:32.530
An example of where it happens
is in this organism, E. coli.

01:00:32.530 --> 01:00:34.400
So I'll just ask you
to raise your hands,

01:00:34.400 --> 01:00:38.390
how many when I say like E. coli
feel really good about E. coli?

