01:01:02.790 --> 01:01:05.850
On the other hand it can cause
enterohemorrhagic E. coli,

01:01:05.850 --> 01:01:07.650
which we heard
about earlier today.

01:01:07.650 --> 01:01:09.632
Terrible diseases, kill people.

01:01:09.632 --> 01:01:12.090
And it turns out that part of
the reason we feel conflicted

01:01:12.090 --> 01:01:15.630
is because E. coli can acquire
genes through horizontal gene

01:01:15.630 --> 01:01:20.340
transfer that make it very, very
virulent and very dangerous.

01:01:20.340 --> 01:01:26.390
So once again, E. coli is
not E. coli, is not E. coli.

01:01:26.390 --> 01:01:28.390
So microbes can
certainly evolve.

01:01:28.390 --> 01:01:28.990
We know that.

01:01:28.990 --> 01:01:31.870
We know microbes can acquire
genes through horizontal gene

01:01:31.870 --> 01:01:33.010
transfer.

01:01:33.010 --> 01:01:35.620
We've talked about how it's a
little difficult to measure.

01:01:35.620 --> 01:01:37.630
But one of the things
that we realize

01:01:37.630 --> 01:01:39.910
is that not only can
microbes evolve over

01:01:39.910 --> 01:01:43.300
time scales of ten of
years, or hundreds of years,

01:01:43.300 --> 01:01:44.480
or millennia.

01:01:44.480 --> 01:01:47.600
But they can actually
evolve in real time.

01:01:47.600 --> 01:01:50.120
And in order to evaluate
that, our laboratory

01:01:50.120 --> 01:01:53.720
studies patients undergoing
bone marrow transplantation.

01:01:53.720 --> 01:01:57.200
Bone marrow transplantation is
a potentially curative therapy

01:01:57.200 --> 01:02:00.270
for patients with
refractory malignancies.

01:02:00.270 --> 01:02:03.050
So cancers like
leukemia and lymphoma.

01:02:03.050 --> 01:02:04.550
It's a really
intensive treatment

01:02:04.550 --> 01:02:06.617
and it has a very high
complication rate.

01:02:06.617 --> 01:02:08.450
But to take you through
the general process.

01:02:08.450 --> 01:02:09.740
We have a patient.

01:02:09.740 --> 01:02:12.440
We give them a lot of
high dose chemotherapy.

01:02:12.440 --> 01:02:15.060
Often we'll also give
them radiation therapy.

01:02:15.060 --> 01:02:18.900
This renders them much reduced
in their cancer burden,

01:02:18.900 --> 01:02:21.470
but it also means that all of
their rapidly dividing cells,

01:02:21.470 --> 01:02:23.219
including the red blood
cells, white blood

01:02:23.219 --> 01:02:26.840
cells, and platelets basically
poop out for a period of time.

01:02:26.840 --> 01:02:29.300
In order to rescue
them we give them

01:02:29.300 --> 01:02:30.920
hematopoietic stem
cells that are

01:02:30.920 --> 01:02:32.630
obtained from a healthy donor.

01:02:32.630 --> 01:02:34.799
And classically, we obtain
these from the pelvis.

01:02:34.799 --> 01:02:36.590
And so that's why it's
called a bone marrow

01:02:36.590 --> 01:02:40.480
transplant because we took
the marrow out of the bone.

01:02:40.480 --> 01:02:42.445
We give these stem
cells to the recipient

01:02:42.445 --> 01:02:45.070
and then we sit around and wait
while a whole new immune system

01:02:45.070 --> 01:02:47.494
develops, which is
kind of amazing.

01:02:47.494 --> 01:02:49.660
But as you can imagine,
over the course of this time

01:02:49.660 --> 01:02:51.750
these patients are
very immunosuppressed.

01:02:51.750 --> 01:02:56.280
They were exposed to a lot
of potential antibiotics, et

01:02:56.280 --> 01:02:59.950
cetera, to try to both prevent
them from getting infections

01:02:59.950 --> 01:03:01.450
and to empirically
treat them when

01:03:01.450 --> 01:03:04.120
they get things like fevers.

01:03:04.120 --> 01:03:07.040
Because they're exposed to
so many of these compounds

01:03:07.040 --> 01:03:10.360
their microbiomes are
for sure under siege.

01:03:10.360 --> 01:03:13.660
And this is an example of a
hospital patient at Stanford

01:03:13.660 --> 01:03:15.280
who underwent bone
marrow transplant

01:03:15.280 --> 01:03:17.800
or hematopoietic
cell transplantation.

01:03:17.800 --> 01:03:20.170
These are time points
after transplantation,

01:03:20.170 --> 01:03:24.090
so A is before the BMT, and
then B, C, and D are after.

01:03:24.090 --> 01:03:26.620
And what you can see
is there microorganisms

01:03:26.620 --> 01:03:28.280
basically go away.

01:03:28.280 --> 01:03:30.550
This is a stacked bar
histogram relative abundance

01:03:30.550 --> 01:03:32.030
on the y-axis.

01:03:32.030 --> 01:03:35.430
And you can see that that blue
organism seems to take over.

01:03:35.430 --> 01:03:39.470
That blue organism happens
to be bacteroides caccae.

01:03:39.470 --> 01:03:41.210
And so two talented
graduate students

01:03:41.210 --> 01:03:43.310
in my lab, Alex
Beshara and Eli Moss,

01:03:43.310 --> 01:03:46.050
asked this question:
how does this occur?

01:03:46.050 --> 01:03:48.650
Why does that organism win?

01:03:48.650 --> 01:03:52.570
It must be particularly fit.

01:03:52.570 --> 01:03:55.980
Furthermore they said, well,
maybe gene transfer or gene

01:03:55.980 --> 01:03:59.580
movement makes this organism
particularly evolutionarily

01:03:59.580 --> 01:04:00.480
fit.

01:04:00.480 --> 01:04:02.460
And they knew that
measuring this gene transfer

01:04:02.460 --> 01:04:06.130
was difficult. Part of
the reason it's difficult

01:04:06.130 --> 01:04:07.810
is because if we
simplify that toy

01:04:07.810 --> 01:04:10.840
diagram into another
representation what you can see

01:04:10.840 --> 01:04:13.900
here is that we can't figure
out whether the right path is

01:04:13.900 --> 01:04:19.760
ARC, or ARD, BRD, or BRD.

01:04:19.760 --> 01:04:22.790
What they decided to do was to
use a technology that actually

01:04:22.790 --> 01:04:26.240
was commercially available
but no computational approach

01:04:26.240 --> 01:04:30.020
existed to apply this
technology in microbiomes.

01:04:30.020 --> 01:04:32.120
And what this
technology roughly does

01:04:32.120 --> 01:04:37.130
is allows you to trace a
trail through the right path.

01:04:37.130 --> 01:04:39.130
In so doing, they found
some intriguing results,

01:04:39.130 --> 01:04:41.990
which I'll share with you.

01:04:41.990 --> 01:04:43.490
I'm going to show
you the genome,

01:04:43.490 --> 01:04:47.690
or a piece of the genome
of this organism in blue.

01:04:47.690 --> 01:04:49.530
This is what a regular
assembly looks like.

01:04:49.530 --> 01:04:51.177
This is 1/6 of the genome.

01:04:51.177 --> 01:04:53.510
And what you can see, for
those different time points A,

01:04:53.510 --> 01:04:56.190
B, C, and D is you
have a lot of holes.

01:04:56.190 --> 01:04:58.550
So it's not contiguous.

01:04:58.550 --> 01:05:00.830
When they applied
their new method

01:05:00.830 --> 01:05:02.750
they ended up with
these blue bars, so

01:05:02.750 --> 01:05:06.120
a much more contiguous genome.

01:05:06.120 --> 01:05:09.190
What this allowed them
to do was the following.

01:05:09.190 --> 01:05:11.860
They were able to
identify this huge segment

01:05:11.860 --> 01:05:16.600
of 60 kilobase pairs of
DNA that actually popped

01:05:16.600 --> 01:05:18.730
into the genome
between time point

01:05:18.730 --> 01:05:23.230
C and time point D. This
is horizontal gene transfer

01:05:23.230 --> 01:05:24.360
in a clinical time scale.

01:05:24.360 --> 01:05:27.880
This happened over the course
of days and weeks, not months.

01:05:27.880 --> 01:05:29.830
So suddenly, we can
measure genes being

01:05:29.830 --> 01:05:33.200
transferred between organisms.

01:05:33.200 --> 01:05:35.930
Finally, they were
able to identify

01:05:35.930 --> 01:05:38.300
insertion sequences,
or small sequences that

01:05:38.300 --> 01:05:39.770
can jump around a genome.

01:05:39.770 --> 01:05:42.570
So jumping genes as we
heard about earlier.

01:05:42.570 --> 01:05:47.230
This particular jumping gene was
absent in time points A and B

01:05:47.230 --> 01:05:54.420
and present in time points C and
D. And these are the results.

01:05:54.420 --> 01:05:57.720
You can see I've got time
points B, C, and D here.

01:05:57.720 --> 01:06:03.450
The gene ends up in that center,
which is listed as the IS.

01:06:03.450 --> 01:06:05.640
And you can see what
happens to the right.

01:06:05.640 --> 01:06:09.000
To the right of that
gene what you see is

01:06:09.000 --> 01:06:13.510
the genes just
upstream are turned on.

01:06:13.510 --> 01:06:15.230
And so whereas in
time point B you

01:06:15.230 --> 01:06:17.370
don't see a lot of
expression of that gene.

01:06:17.370 --> 01:06:18.930
Those genes are off.

01:06:18.930 --> 01:06:22.380
In time point C and D once that
insertion sequence pops in,

01:06:22.380 --> 01:06:25.260
suddenly you've flipped a switch
and this antibiotic resistance

01:06:25.260 --> 01:06:27.910
gene turns on.

01:06:27.910 --> 01:06:30.480
So no genes were
acquired or lost.

01:06:30.480 --> 01:06:32.740
This jumping gene
just moved around

01:06:32.740 --> 01:06:36.450
and acts as a
random light switch.

01:06:36.450 --> 01:06:38.670
So I'll just end
by reminding you,

01:06:38.670 --> 01:06:40.890
we have trillions of
neighbors and our microbes

01:06:40.890 --> 01:06:43.290
are often good.

01:06:43.290 --> 01:06:46.320
Context matters and there
are perils associated

01:06:46.320 --> 01:06:48.270
with simplified microbiomes.

01:06:48.270 --> 01:06:52.510
They may increase our disease
susceptibility our microbes are

01:06:52.510 --> 01:06:56.830
under siege: antiseptics,
antibiotics, industrialization,

01:06:56.830 --> 01:07:01.760
and many have argued
simplified diets, low in fiber.

01:07:01.760 --> 01:07:03.440
Our microbes are
alive and changing

01:07:03.440 --> 01:07:05.930
and they are steadily evolving
through mutations and gene

01:07:05.930 --> 01:07:07.690
transfer.

01:07:07.690 --> 01:07:10.840
Finally, microbial evolution
can happen on a clinical time

01:07:10.840 --> 01:07:11.540
scale.

01:07:11.540 --> 01:07:13.540
I showed you evidence of
a shape shifting genome

01:07:13.540 --> 01:07:15.460
and antibiotic resistance.

01:07:15.460 --> 01:07:18.280
So with that, I'll thank
my lab, thank all of you,

01:07:18.280 --> 01:07:20.520
and I'm happy to join the
panel for some questions.

01:07:20.520 --> 01:07:24.020
