and over again by these crises
that are very time sensitive.

01:13:33.190 --> 01:13:36.280
And then we see somebody go
before Congress and asking

01:13:36.280 --> 01:13:38.639
for a billion dollars
to develop a vaccine.

01:13:38.639 --> 01:13:40.180
Well, then all the
information that's

01:13:40.180 --> 01:13:42.880
associated with that endeavor
starts getting clamped down

01:13:42.880 --> 01:13:44.830
and becoming proprietary.

01:13:44.830 --> 01:13:47.487
And we had huge trouble
getting information

01:13:47.487 --> 01:13:49.570
on what was happening with
the Ebola on the ground

01:13:49.570 --> 01:13:52.060
as well as Zika because
of some of the overlays

01:13:52.060 --> 01:13:54.760
that were involved
with that process.

01:13:54.760 --> 01:13:57.790
And I would ask the audience
the honest to goodness question,

01:13:57.790 --> 01:14:01.770
do we have a vaccine available
on the market for Ebola?

01:14:01.770 --> 01:14:04.017
Where did that funding go?

01:14:04.017 --> 01:14:05.600
Why don't we have a
vaccine for Ebola?

01:14:05.600 --> 01:14:07.100
Why don't we have
one for West Nile?

01:14:07.100 --> 01:14:09.080
Why don't we have one for SARS?

01:14:09.080 --> 01:14:10.582
Why don't we have one for MERS?

01:14:10.582 --> 01:14:11.540
Why don't we have one--

01:14:11.540 --> 01:14:14.020
I mean so if you
think about this--

01:14:14.020 --> 01:14:17.960
and Sanofi backed out of the
Zika vaccine production, right?

01:14:17.960 --> 01:14:22.430
So where are we going
with all of this.

01:14:22.430 --> 01:14:25.700
Allow me to be the curmudgeon
here and maybe the cynic,

01:14:25.700 --> 01:14:29.000
but we have real
problems with how

01:14:29.000 --> 01:14:31.237
do we share information
and do the right thing.

01:14:31.237 --> 01:14:33.320
And that's why I'm very
animated about this issue,

01:14:33.320 --> 01:14:37.190
is that I've seen it play out
over, and over, and over again.

01:14:37.190 --> 01:14:39.370
So to me that is the
big research question.

01:14:39.370 --> 01:14:40.850
- OK, Yeah, I agree.

01:14:40.850 --> 01:14:42.620
There is there's an
organization called

01:14:42.620 --> 01:14:46.270
CEPI that was founded
after the Ebola outbreak

01:14:46.270 --> 01:14:50.090
and it's an effort to
finance clinical trials

01:14:50.090 --> 01:14:54.170
to get some of these potentially
emerging pandemic infections

01:14:54.170 --> 01:14:55.960
to develop vaccines for them.

01:14:55.960 --> 01:14:57.824
And so that if
something happens,

01:14:57.824 --> 01:14:59.990
there's an accelerated
pipeline to get vaccines out.

01:14:59.990 --> 01:15:03.051
It's a hard problem to know
which pathogens you choose

01:15:03.051 --> 01:15:04.050
and all of those things.

01:15:04.050 --> 01:15:07.220
But it's certainly something
we're going to need to tackle.

01:15:07.220 --> 01:15:08.660
OK, so I'm going to open it.

01:15:08.660 --> 01:15:11.480
Up if you come and line
up behind the microphone

01:15:11.480 --> 01:15:15.230
please state your name and
then ask your question.

01:15:15.230 --> 01:15:20.210
And we have about 10
minutes for questions.

01:15:20.210 --> 01:15:22.010
- Paul [INAUDIBLE] from Tuffs.

01:15:22.010 --> 01:15:26.360
Jim, I'd like to ask you
about that whole half, maybe

01:15:26.360 --> 01:15:29.281
more of the environment
that wasn't talked about

01:15:29.281 --> 01:15:30.030
and that zoonosis.

01:15:32.840 --> 01:15:38.360
We aren't coupling with
the veterinary community,

01:15:38.360 --> 01:15:42.890
with the zoos, or with all of
the animal side of the kingdom

01:15:42.890 --> 01:15:47.600
here, subhuman,
blah, blah, blah.

01:15:47.600 --> 01:15:50.780
It seems to me that part
of what you're doing really

01:15:50.780 --> 01:15:53.910
needs to be including
that part as well.

01:15:53.910 --> 01:15:57.230
You know, for example, the
Journal of Emerging Diseases

01:15:57.230 --> 01:16:01.070
from the CDC has been doing
that for the last 10 or 20 years

01:16:01.070 --> 01:16:04.076
and in terms of making
those connections.

01:16:04.076 --> 01:16:07.700
Any comments on that?

01:16:07.700 --> 01:16:10.870
- Do you want me to respond now?

01:16:10.870 --> 01:16:14.312
- Let's have a few questions
and then we'll answer them.

01:16:14.312 --> 01:16:16.020
- This is sort of a
complicated question.

01:16:16.020 --> 01:16:17.490
My name is Alyssa
Goodman and I'm

01:16:17.490 --> 01:16:19.490
a professor in the astronomy
department and also

01:16:19.490 --> 01:16:22.440
the other science director
here at Radcliffe.

01:16:22.440 --> 01:16:24.700
And my question actually
sort of concerns astronomy.

01:16:24.700 --> 01:16:27.360
So in astronomy we're known
for sharing our economically

01:16:27.360 --> 01:16:28.875
valueless data--

01:16:28.875 --> 01:16:30.090
[LAUGHTER]

01:16:30.090 --> 01:16:31.524
--very well, actually.

01:16:31.524 --> 01:16:32.940
And so I was asked
a few years ago

01:16:32.940 --> 01:16:36.450
to give a talk at something
called Sage Bionetworks which

01:16:36.450 --> 01:16:38.954
is where a number of the
pharmaceutical companies,

01:16:38.954 --> 01:16:40.620
thanks to the efforts
of Stephen Friend,

01:16:40.620 --> 01:16:43.830
have volunteered to give
away the data that were not

01:16:43.830 --> 01:16:45.840
useful in drug trials.

01:16:45.840 --> 01:16:48.750
And it turns out that
this is really helpful.

01:16:48.750 --> 01:16:52.470
And so I'm just curious whether
in the world of epidemiology

01:16:52.470 --> 01:16:53.850
there's some equivalent of that?

01:16:53.850 --> 01:16:56.880
Where some fraction of the
data could be made public

01:16:56.880 --> 01:16:59.674
rather than all or nothing?

01:16:59.674 --> 01:17:01.018
- Thank you.

01:17:01.018 --> 01:17:04.140
- I'd like thank the panel
for your wonderful talks.

01:17:04.140 --> 01:17:09.120
Specifically, I'd like
to ask about what I think

01:17:09.120 --> 01:17:10.340
is an elephant in the room.

01:17:10.340 --> 01:17:12.270
I loved Professor Bhatt's--

01:17:12.270 --> 01:17:14.580
Dr. Bhatt's picture
of the elephants.

01:17:14.580 --> 01:17:18.150
And that elephant is results
from the intersection

01:17:18.150 --> 01:17:21.420
of genetic engineering and
perhaps particularly CRISPR.

01:17:21.420 --> 01:17:24.660
Our CRISPR speaker talked
about super villains.

01:17:24.660 --> 01:17:28.050
And so my elephant
is the intersection

01:17:28.050 --> 01:17:31.140
of genetic engineering,
particularly maybe

01:17:31.140 --> 01:17:34.650
CRISPR powered genetic
engineering and bioterrorism,

01:17:34.650 --> 01:17:37.830
and how that relates
to your interests

01:17:37.830 --> 01:17:40.665
in monitoring and
responding to health crises.

01:17:44.440 --> 01:17:45.440
- I'm Ann Patterson.

01:17:45.440 --> 01:17:49.130
I work in an organic vegetable
farm, which shows my bias.

01:17:49.130 --> 01:17:53.480
Can you give me any
guidance on how to improve

01:17:53.480 --> 01:17:55.769
our microbiome by what we eat?

01:17:55.769 --> 01:17:57.560
I know you said it was
in the ground water,

01:17:57.560 --> 01:18:00.670
but there must be something
we can do about it.

01:18:00.670 --> 01:18:02.630
- OK, thank you.

01:18:02.630 --> 01:18:06.610
So we'll start with the
question for Jim about zoonosis

01:18:06.610 --> 01:18:09.040
and the importance
of monitoring,

01:18:09.040 --> 01:18:11.705
being involved with agriculture
and zoos and this kind

01:18:11.705 --> 01:18:13.840
of thing.

01:18:13.840 --> 01:18:16.960
- So Tracy McNamara from
West Nile virus days

01:18:16.960 --> 01:18:19.430
in the Bronx Zoo, she
was the one way back

01:18:19.430 --> 01:18:22.520
when who introduced me to
the concept of one health.

01:18:22.520 --> 01:18:23.390
So we definitely do.

01:18:23.390 --> 01:18:28.100
I was remiss in mentioning that,
so thanks for calling that out.

01:18:28.100 --> 01:18:31.070
When we led the
tracking of H5N1 when

01:18:31.070 --> 01:18:32.600
it was spreading
throughout Asia,

01:18:32.600 --> 01:18:34.250
one of the leading
indicators that we

01:18:34.250 --> 01:18:38.720
knew that H5N1 was probably
spreading up into Russia

01:18:38.720 --> 01:18:41.720
was the bird die off reports.

01:18:41.720 --> 01:18:45.350
We're absolutely on that
page and on board with that.

01:18:45.350 --> 01:18:48.020
And honestly, huge
parts of the network

01:18:48.020 --> 01:18:50.510
that I monitor on the human
side are veterinarians

01:18:50.510 --> 01:18:52.140
and our veterinary researchers.

01:18:52.140 --> 01:18:53.464
So we're very close to that.

01:18:53.464 --> 01:18:54.880
So thank you for
calling that out.

01:18:57.900 --> 01:19:02.430
- So, the next question was
about giving away seemingly

01:19:02.430 --> 01:19:06.390
non-useful data and whether
we could do a better job.

01:19:06.390 --> 01:19:08.860
I mean, I think we definitely
can do a better job.

01:19:08.860 --> 01:19:10.950
And there needs to
be better incentives.

01:19:10.950 --> 01:19:14.250
And their responsibility
by researchers like we

01:19:14.250 --> 01:19:16.530
saw earlier today to
take it upon themselves

01:19:16.530 --> 01:19:18.330
to do a better job with this.

01:19:18.330 --> 01:19:21.570
It's very hard as an academic
because your incentives

01:19:21.570 --> 01:19:24.390
are squarely in publishing.

01:19:24.390 --> 01:19:26.130
And even if it's
not for you, you

01:19:26.130 --> 01:19:27.900
want your PhD
students and post-docs

01:19:27.900 --> 01:19:30.066
to get their publications out.

01:19:30.066 --> 01:19:31.440
Jess do you have
opinions about--

01:19:31.440 --> 01:19:33.950
I know you have opinions
about this, so I will ask you.

01:19:33.950 --> 01:19:36.170
- So I have one lovely example.

01:19:36.170 --> 01:19:39.000
There's a chap called
Hugo Lopez-Gatell who

01:19:39.000 --> 01:19:41.627
was a PhD student
at Johns Hopkins

01:19:41.627 --> 01:19:43.710
and went to the director
of epidemiology in Mexico

01:19:43.710 --> 01:19:46.680
and asked for their childhood
infection and other data.

01:19:46.680 --> 01:19:49.240
And the director of
epidemiology told him no.

01:19:49.240 --> 01:19:52.140
And later, Hugo Lopez-Gatell
became the director

01:19:52.140 --> 01:19:53.300
of epidemiology in Mexico.

01:19:53.300 --> 01:19:54.270
[LAUGHTER]

01:19:54.270 --> 01:19:56.590
And all that data is
freely available online.

01:19:56.590 --> 01:19:58.620
And one of my brilliant
ex graduate students,

01:19:58.620 --> 01:20:01.131
Ayesha Mahmud, who's in
the audience here I think,

01:20:01.131 --> 01:20:02.880
used all that data for
one of her chapters

01:20:02.880 --> 01:20:03.713
of her dissertation.

01:20:03.713 --> 01:20:05.310
I think is increasingly moving.

01:20:05.310 --> 01:20:06.820
The Pan-American
Health Organization

01:20:06.820 --> 01:20:08.194
are real leaders
in this respect.

01:20:08.194 --> 01:20:11.345
So many of those countries
share so much of the data.

01:20:11.345 --> 01:20:12.720
And many countries
are relatively

01:20:12.720 --> 01:20:15.700
relaxed about sharing their
death records, causes of death.

01:20:15.700 --> 01:20:17.970
And so there's incredibly
rich data there

01:20:17.970 --> 01:20:19.640
which has yet to be mined.

01:20:19.640 --> 01:20:21.060
I'm the optimist.

01:20:21.060 --> 01:20:24.240
I think that the world
is moving towards this.

01:20:24.240 --> 01:20:27.300
And the generation of scientists
that's being trained now

01:20:27.300 --> 01:20:29.010
is thinking deeply
about these questions

01:20:29.010 --> 01:20:30.520
and tackling these questions.

01:20:30.520 --> 01:20:32.520
- And I think digital
platforms for data sharing

01:20:32.520 --> 01:20:34.560
are going to be key, especially
for the kind of field

01:20:34.560 --> 01:20:36.120
epidemiology that we've
been talking about.

01:20:36.120 --> 01:20:37.536
Once things are
digitized we don't

01:20:37.536 --> 01:20:40.110
have to go and find
somebody's hand-drawn map

01:20:40.110 --> 01:20:43.200
and things can be collated,
and aggregated, and shared

01:20:43.200 --> 01:20:44.040
more easily.

01:20:44.040 --> 01:20:45.679
Do you have comments on this?

01:20:45.679 --> 01:20:47.970
- I think it's critically
important that those data are

01:20:47.970 --> 01:20:50.010
shared, but I also
think we need to support

01:20:50.010 --> 01:20:52.990
the centralized resources
that host the data sharing.

01:20:52.990 --> 01:20:58.260
So from our perspective, we
have open sharing mechanisms

01:20:58.260 --> 01:21:00.510
and approaches for
genomic data, but our data

01:21:00.510 --> 01:21:04.655
are increasingly growing in
size and are only accelerating.

01:21:04.655 --> 01:21:06.780
Right now in the United
States the National Library

01:21:06.780 --> 01:21:09.720
of Medicine is charged with
storing all of these data,

01:21:09.720 --> 01:21:12.940
but are quite chronically
underfunded for that purpose.

01:21:12.940 --> 01:21:15.810
And so I think as we think about
generating these data, which

01:21:15.810 --> 01:21:18.550
we most certainly
must and should share,

01:21:18.550 --> 01:21:21.300
we need to think about how
we create infrastructures

01:21:21.300 --> 01:21:22.493
that allow that.

01:21:22.493 --> 01:21:24.860
- Great.

01:21:24.860 --> 01:21:28.130
On the question of genetic
engineering and bioterrorism,

01:21:28.130 --> 01:21:30.410
I will pass this
to Jim in a second.

01:21:30.410 --> 01:21:32.420
I would just say
that like our ability

01:21:32.420 --> 01:21:35.000
to prepare for
pandemics globally

01:21:35.000 --> 01:21:37.370
and our ability to
detect things that

01:21:37.370 --> 01:21:39.500
are going to become
a big problem,

01:21:39.500 --> 01:21:41.960
I think the answer
often is health system

01:21:41.960 --> 01:21:45.410
strengthening, good access to
health care in low and middle

01:21:45.410 --> 01:21:46.130
income settings.

01:21:46.130 --> 01:21:48.110
And it comes back to
that over and over again.

01:21:48.110 --> 01:21:49.700
We can't detect
anything if we don't

01:21:49.700 --> 01:21:52.640
have good data from the field.

01:21:52.640 --> 01:21:56.480
But I'm not an expert in
the bioterrorism field

01:21:56.480 --> 01:21:59.540
so I'll ask Jim if he'd
like to comment on that one.

01:21:59.540 --> 01:22:02.360
- So the way that we detect
unusual events is we're just

01:22:02.360 --> 01:22:05.420
looking for unusual
disease, or unusual events

01:22:05.420 --> 01:22:06.560
that are recorded.

01:22:06.560 --> 01:22:10.580
Unusual social disruption
where we don't expect it.

01:22:10.580 --> 01:22:14.750
And then we ask the questions,
then it becomes very forensic.

01:22:14.750 --> 01:22:17.120
The hard part here is
putting things in context.

01:22:17.120 --> 01:22:18.750
And we have a habit
in this country,

01:22:18.750 --> 01:22:22.340
and this goes back
for decades now,

01:22:22.340 --> 01:22:23.936
of worrying about biotechnology.

01:22:23.936 --> 01:22:26.060
So for those of you who
are old enough in the, room

01:22:26.060 --> 01:22:28.040
you remember the
concern about DNA

01:22:28.040 --> 01:22:32.090
recombinant technology in the
'70s, and The Andromeda Strain

01:22:32.090 --> 01:22:34.190
movie and how it got
everybody spun up

01:22:34.190 --> 01:22:35.600
about having
physical containment

01:22:35.600 --> 01:22:38.370
level for facilities be created
here in the United States.

01:22:38.370 --> 01:22:41.780
So this is a longstanding
thing, and then we

01:22:41.780 --> 01:22:43.890
have Hollywood
driving the memes.

01:22:43.890 --> 01:22:45.930
So we love to scare
ourselves, we do.

01:22:45.930 --> 01:22:47.250
It's our society.

01:22:47.250 --> 01:22:51.140
And so if you watch these
events though for 25 years

01:22:51.140 --> 01:22:53.450
and you become a
curmudgeon like me,

01:22:53.450 --> 01:22:59.240
you realize that we tend to blow
things out of proportion a lot.

01:22:59.240 --> 01:23:01.490
So earlier we had a
map posted on Zika

01:23:01.490 --> 01:23:03.560
that highlighted
literally half the United

01:23:03.560 --> 01:23:05.720
States at risk for Zika.

01:23:05.720 --> 01:23:07.250
And we had to
spend a lot of time

01:23:07.250 --> 01:23:09.990
around behind the scenes
calming people down and saying,

01:23:09.990 --> 01:23:14.040
listen, the probability of a
sustained epidemic of Zika is--

01:23:14.040 --> 01:23:16.280
OK, let's be cool about this.

01:23:16.280 --> 01:23:19.170
All right, let's be careful
and put things in context.

01:23:19.170 --> 01:23:21.380
So I think we do have,
when it comes to CRISPR,

01:23:21.380 --> 01:23:23.810
I think we need to slow down.

01:23:23.810 --> 01:23:26.000
Let's listen to the researchers.

01:23:26.000 --> 01:23:28.040
Let's listen and give
them an opportunity

01:23:28.040 --> 01:23:30.100
to engage in the discourse.

01:23:30.100 --> 01:23:32.840
And let's not go a little
overboard as we classically do.

01:23:32.840 --> 01:23:35.780
My last point would be we
can't even handle game playing

01:23:35.780 --> 01:23:38.930
level one, why are we
trying to jack it up to game

01:23:38.930 --> 01:23:41.240
playing level number 50?

01:23:41.240 --> 01:23:43.460
So we're having a very
hard time managing

01:23:43.460 --> 01:23:46.880
the things that are presented
to us by mother nature.

01:23:46.880 --> 01:23:50.580
Why do we have to go off
into science fiction land?

01:23:50.580 --> 01:23:54.210
So I really, I'm sorry for
taking the pragmatic point

01:23:54.210 --> 01:23:56.490
of view, but that's
really after 25 years

01:23:56.490 --> 01:23:58.920
that's what it's left me.

01:23:58.920 --> 01:24:01.410
- Yeah, and I think
preparing for a pandemic

01:24:01.410 --> 01:24:04.050
means preparing for
local epidemics first.

01:24:04.050 --> 01:24:07.010
So pandemics start local and
we have to think about it

01:24:07.010 --> 01:24:08.670
in that context.

01:24:08.670 --> 01:24:11.650
So the last question and
then if we have time,

01:24:11.650 --> 01:24:15.210
we'll take a few more, was
about microbiome and diet.

01:24:15.210 --> 01:24:17.230
That was for Ami.

01:24:17.230 --> 01:24:19.397
- So I think obviously we're
interested in improving

01:24:19.397 --> 01:24:21.188
our microbiome, and
I'm glad at least there

01:24:21.188 --> 01:24:23.820
are some people in the audience
who resonated with that.

01:24:23.820 --> 01:24:27.240
There's limited prospective
data on this topic.

01:24:27.240 --> 01:24:31.830
Certainly many espouse eating
diverse fiber rich diet

01:24:31.830 --> 01:24:36.790
as a method for potentially
returning to an increased

01:24:36.790 --> 01:24:38.520
diversity of the microbiome.

01:24:38.520 --> 01:24:40.140
I certainly think,
as a physician,

01:24:40.140 --> 01:24:42.630
minimizing exposure to
unnecessary antibiotics

01:24:42.630 --> 01:24:43.620
is critical.

01:24:43.620 --> 01:24:46.500
And I've seen certainly a
shift from five years ago

01:24:46.500 --> 01:24:49.550
when you have sniffles, you go
in, you ask for your Z-Pack.

01:24:49.550 --> 01:24:51.880
To people coming in
and really saying,

01:24:51.880 --> 01:24:54.000
well, I don't think I
need a Z-Pack, which

01:24:54.000 --> 01:24:55.860
I think is part of the answer.

01:24:55.860 --> 01:24:57.840
Obviously we have
antibiotic use that's

01:24:57.840 --> 01:25:01.230
broad scale in, for example,
the livestock industry.

01:25:01.230 --> 01:25:05.390
And you heard a little bit about
other household antimicrobials.

01:25:05.390 --> 01:25:07.830
You know, curtailing
use of these

01:25:07.830 --> 01:25:11.280
is much more of a global
issue than a local issue.

01:25:11.280 --> 01:25:15.240
Bu I think it begins with
consumers asking what

01:25:15.240 --> 01:25:18.660
the potential for harm
is with novel agents that

01:25:18.660 --> 01:25:21.120
are introduced into
the commercial sector.

01:25:21.120 --> 01:25:23.940
And so I think being smart
consumers can certainly

01:25:23.940 --> 01:25:24.824
contribute.

01:25:24.824 --> 01:25:26.490
But I think those are
some of the things

01:25:26.490 --> 01:25:29.025
that we can do as we
consider our microbiome.

01:25:29.025 --> 01:25:30.900
And I think the first
step toward improvement

01:25:30.900 --> 01:25:33.500
is obviously awareness.

01:25:33.500 --> 01:25:34.130
- OK.

01:25:34.130 --> 01:25:37.400
I've been told we have one more
time for one more question.

01:25:37.400 --> 01:25:39.920
- Cynthia [INAUDIBLE]
from Brandeis University.

01:25:39.920 --> 01:25:42.890
And I was wondering--

01:25:42.890 --> 01:25:46.190
I think maybe this question is
mostly for Jim-- but are you

01:25:46.190 --> 01:25:48.860
doing any work with
tuberculosis because it's

01:25:48.860 --> 01:25:51.410
the leading infectious
killer in the world,

01:25:51.410 --> 01:25:54.680
and between 30% and
40% of all deaths

01:25:54.680 --> 01:25:57.110
due to antimicrobial
resistant bugs

01:25:57.110 --> 01:25:59.220
are due to drug resistant TB.

01:25:59.220 --> 01:26:02.210
And do we not track it
anymore because we just

01:26:02.210 --> 01:26:04.760
know that it's endemic and it's
going to kill a ton of people

01:26:04.760 --> 01:26:05.990
and given up on them?

01:26:05.990 --> 01:26:09.740
Or what's the scenario from
your perspective of pretty much

01:26:09.740 --> 01:26:13.810
any of your work, but I
think maybe especially Jim.

01:26:13.810 --> 01:26:16.500
- Well, so our bias
here is we look

01:26:16.500 --> 01:26:21.600
at abrupt shifts in
indicators that that show us

01:26:21.600 --> 01:26:24.600
that a community is suddenly
experiencing something

01:26:24.600 --> 01:26:26.330
that's acutely happening.

01:26:26.330 --> 01:26:30.110
And in the tuberculosis
world, like with HIV, malaria,

01:26:30.110 --> 01:26:32.280
and so these other
endemic diseases

01:26:32.280 --> 01:26:34.770
in endemic areas
of the world, we

01:26:34.770 --> 01:26:37.140
see very calm
disruption patterns.

01:26:37.140 --> 01:26:38.730
So these are
communities that are

01:26:38.730 --> 01:26:40.290
used to dealing
with these issues,

01:26:40.290 --> 01:26:42.630
they're de-sensitized
even though there's

01:26:42.630 --> 01:26:44.220
a lot of mortality.

01:26:44.220 --> 01:26:47.090
What we do see are cases where--

01:26:47.090 --> 01:26:49.030
and we know it's just
the tip of the iceberg.

01:26:49.030 --> 01:26:51.529
I mean, we have data problems
just like everybody else does.

01:26:51.529 --> 01:26:55.530
But where an XDR TB will show
up in a clinic in South Africa

01:26:55.530 --> 01:26:57.239
and people will realize
that, oh my gosh,

01:26:57.239 --> 01:26:59.363
we're dealing with a patient
that can't be treated.

01:26:59.363 --> 01:27:01.080
And then people
evacuate the facility,

01:27:01.080 --> 01:27:03.510
potentially spreading
that into the community.

01:27:03.510 --> 01:27:06.330
And so we've detected
that periodically.

01:27:06.330 --> 01:27:09.030
We know there's a lot
that we don't detect.

01:27:09.030 --> 01:27:10.420
And yeah, it's a huge issue.

01:27:10.420 --> 01:27:13.890
I mean, we've all discussed
the issues of access

01:27:13.890 --> 01:27:16.800
to data, which kind of
drives everything and drives

01:27:16.800 --> 01:27:17.880
our awareness.

01:27:17.880 --> 01:27:19.590
But the classic mantra
in public health

01:27:19.590 --> 01:27:21.465
is, if you don't report
it, it doesn't exist.

01:27:24.850 --> 01:27:27.120
- And I would just
add that there

01:27:27.120 --> 01:27:34.440
are significant pushes to
end TB, and malaria, and HIV.

01:27:34.440 --> 01:27:37.170
And you know we've been talking
about an explosive epidemic

01:27:37.170 --> 01:27:40.560
event, but actually there
are these very long time

01:27:40.560 --> 01:27:42.900
endemic infections that
cause a huge amount

01:27:42.900 --> 01:27:44.610
morbidity and
mortality and continue

01:27:44.610 --> 01:27:47.910
to place enormous economic
burden on low and middle income

01:27:47.910 --> 01:27:48.930
settings.

01:27:48.930 --> 01:27:52.110
Those movements with genomics
and all of the methods

01:27:52.110 --> 01:27:53.490
that we've been
talking about are

01:27:53.490 --> 01:27:56.490
hard for these infections
that have long, chronic latent

01:27:56.490 --> 01:27:57.630
periods.

01:27:57.630 --> 01:28:00.990
But there's certainly
a whole range

01:28:00.990 --> 01:28:03.300
of people who are trying
to push for ultimately

01:28:03.300 --> 01:28:05.610
eradication of those things.

01:28:05.610 --> 01:28:07.980
We've only managed to
eradicate two pathogens.

01:28:07.980 --> 01:28:11.580
We're struggling to do
so for the third, polio.

01:28:11.580 --> 01:28:14.680
But that is definitely
on the agenda,

01:28:14.680 --> 01:28:16.219
I think, for most people.

01:28:16.219 --> 01:28:17.760
It's a really tough
challenge though.

01:28:17.760 --> 01:28:20.700
I don't know if Jess, you
want to talk about TB.

01:28:20.700 --> 01:28:23.120
- I was just going to mention
that genomics as well.

01:28:23.120 --> 01:28:25.380
Although it's very
hard to detect TB

01:28:25.380 --> 01:28:27.210
through case detection
just because it

01:28:27.210 --> 01:28:29.661
is this chronic pathogen.
We can trace back

01:28:29.661 --> 01:28:32.160
by looking at the genomics and
trying to understand patterns

01:28:32.160 --> 01:28:32.760
of spread.

01:28:32.760 --> 01:28:35.040
And that, again, speaks
to health care capacity

01:28:35.040 --> 01:28:36.630
and where you need
reinforcements.

01:28:36.630 --> 01:28:39.030
So it is a hidden
epidemic but it's one

01:28:39.030 --> 01:28:42.102
that we are using the lens
of things like, I mean,

01:28:42.102 --> 01:28:43.560
to use the big data
buzz word again

01:28:43.560 --> 01:28:45.351
is being used to approach
these challenges.

